{"title_page": "Alabama cavefish", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Alabama cavefish\n| status = CR\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{Cite iucn | author = NatureServe | title = ''Speoplatyrhinus poulsoni'' | volume = 2013 | page = e.T20467A19033986 | date = 2013 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2013-1.RLTS.T20467A19033986.en }} Listed as Critically Endangered (CR B1ab(iii)+2ab(iii) v3.1)</ref>\n| image = AlabamaCavefish.jpg\n| genus = Speoplatyrhinus\n| parent_authority = [[John Edward Cooper|J. E. Cooper]] & [[Robert Andrew Kuehne|Kuehne]], 1974\n| species = poulsoni\n| authority = J. E. Cooper & Kuehne, 1974<ref>{{ITIS |id=164397|taxon=''Speoplatyrhinus poulsoni''|accessdate=18 April 2006}}</ref>\n| range_map = File:Alabama Cavefish Range.png\n| range_map_caption = The range map of the Alabama Cavefish.\n}}\n\nThe '''Alabama cavefish''' (''Speoplatyrhinus poulsoni''), is a [[critically endangered]] species of [[Amblyopsidae|amblyopsid cavefish]] found only in underground pools in Key Cave, located in northwestern [[Alabama]], United States in the [[Key Cave National Wildlife Refuge]].<ref name=\"Fishbase\">{{FishBase species |genus=Speoplatyrhinus|species=poulsoni|month= March|year=2006}}</ref> It was discovered underneath a colony of [[gray bat]]s in 1967 by researchers Robert A. Kuehne and John E. Cooper<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Romero|first=Aldemaro|date=1998|title=Threatened fishes of the world: Speoplatyrhinus poulsoni|url=http://link.springer.com/10.1023/A:1007405815580|journal=Environmental Biology of Fishes|volume=53|issue=3|pages=293\u2013294|doi=10.1023/A:1007405815580|via=}}</ref> and [[Species description|scientifically described]] in 1974.<ref name=Cooper1974>Cooper, J.E., and R.A. Kuehne (1974). \"Speoplatyrhinus poulsoni, a New Genus and Species of Subterranean Fish from Alabama.\" Copeia 1974: 486-93.</ref>\n\nOn any single visit to the cave, no more than 10 individuals of this fish have been observed, and scientists estimate fewer than 100 are left.<ref name=iucn/> This fish is believed to be the rarest species of [[cavefish]] in the United States and one of the rarest of all freshwater fish. It exists in a fragile ecosystem based on nutrient-rich [[guano]] of the gray bat.<ref name=\"fws\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fws.gov/ecos/ajax/docs/life_histories/E011.html|title=Alabama Cavefish|publisher=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007234105/http://www.fws.gov/ecos/ajax/docs/life_histories/E011.html|archivedate=7 October 2014|accessdate=12 October 2011}}</ref> Researchers have failed to find the fish in any other location.<ref name=iucn/>\n\nThe only species in its genus, the Alabama cavefish is in danger of extinction. Conservation measures that have been taken to save the species from extinction include protecting the fish under the [[Lacey Act of 1900|Lacey Act]] and limiting human disturbance of Key Cave.\n\n==Habitat and Distribution==\n\nThe Alabama cavefish is one of the rarest [[cavefish]] species in North America. While the specific habitat requirements of the fish are unknown, it is known that the Alabama cavefish is a cave obligate, restricted to [[Key Cave National Wildlife Refuge|Key Cave]] in [[Lauderdale County, Alabama]]. Cave habitats tend to be stable, with drastic changes mainly being associated with the inflow of water. Annual rainfall and flooding in the cave produce changes in water level, temperature, and food availability for the fish. Researchers speculate that the flooding may trigger a hormonal change in the cavefish for growth and reproduction.\n\nSince the discovery of the cavefish, only 9 specimens have been collected (all before 1983). Because very few individuals have been collected and observed and the population is confined to [[Key Cave National Wildlife Refuge|Key Cave]]'','' the Alabama cavefish may be the rarest of the American cavefish and the rarest freshwater fish.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Romero|first=Aldemaro|date=1998|title=Threatened fishes of the world: Speoplatyrhinus poulsoni|url=http://link.springer.com/10.1023/A:1007405815580|journal=Environmental Biology of Fishes|volume=53|issue=3|pages=293\u2013294|doi=10.1023/A:1007405815580|via=}}</ref> \n\nBecause the underground water system in the area is so widespread, it was hoped that the cavefish had dispersed to other sites. However, studies of 120 other caves in the area, conducted since 1977, have failed to locate any other cavefish populations. No more than 10 individuals have been observed on any single visit to the Key Cave and in 36 visits from 1967 to 1998, the average was less than 4 per visit.<ref name=\"iucn\" /> The total number of individuals in the Key Cave population is estimated to be less than 100.<ref name=\"iucn\" /> Initially classified as [[Vulnerable species|vulnerable]] by the [[IUCN]], its status has been gradually upgraded as its extreme rarity became apparent. It is currently considered [[critically endangered]].<ref name=\"iucn\" /> Two reports of these fish in nearby Collier Cave are unconfirmed. Both caves are protected and inaccessible to the public.\n\nBecause its known range is limited to a single cave, the Alabama cavefish has an uncertain future, being threatened by changes in groundwater quality and level, changes in [[aquifer]] characteristics, and diminished organic input. It also may compete with the syntopic [[southern cavefish]] (''Typhlichthys subterraneus''), which is more abundant and aggressive.<ref name=\"fws\" /> Cave crayfish sometimes feed on Alabama cavefish.<ref name=\"fws\" />\n\n==Physiology==\n\nThe Alabama cavefish is up to {{convert|7.2|cm|in|abbr=on}} long and has no eyes or discernible pigmentation,<ref name=\"Fishbase\"/> appearing semitransparent with a slight pink hue. Its large head makes up more than one-third of its length. It is the only species in its genus, and can be distinguished from other cavefish with its very elongated, flattened head with a laterally constricted snout and a terminal mouth. The cavefish lacks pelvic fins, and its fin rays are unbranched with the fin membranes deeply incised between the rays. It has an elaborate system of sensory papillae, arranged in ridges on the head and sides, an adaptation to the dark environment.<ref name=\"fws\"/> The Alabama cavefish has the most highly developed caudal sensory papillae in the Amblyopsidae family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ecos.fws.gov/ecp0/profile/speciesProfile?sId=50|title=Species Profile|website=ecos.fws.gov|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==Diet==\n\nIts diet of [[copepod]]s, [[isopod]]s, [[amphipod]]s, and smaller cavefish is supported by the nutrient-filled bat guano.<ref name=\"fws\"/> It can also survive on other small organisms such as mites, spiders, millipedes, and beetles and other insects.<ref name=\"Outdoor Alabama\">{{cite web|url=http://www.outdooralabama.com/fishing/freshwater/fish/other/cavefish/alabama/|title=Alabama Cavefish|accessdate=9 March 2009|year=2008|publisher=Outdoor Alabama|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090316212948/http://www.outdooralabama.com/fishing/freshwater/fish/other/cavefish/alabama/|archivedate=16 March 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Reproduction==\n\nThere is little information available on the reproductive cycle of the Alabama cavefish. Some speculate that it may reproduce like the [[northern cavefish]] by carrying its young [[Mouthbrooder|inside its mouth]] to be incubated.<ref name=\"Outdoor Alabama\"/> The Alabama cavefish, like most fish, utilizes seasonal cues to trigger hormonal changes that lead to its growth and reproduction. While most fish rely on a large change in water temperature or photoperiod, the Alabama cavefish rely on flooding of the cave in the winter and spring.'''<ref name=\"fws\" />''' This results in an increase in flow of water into the cave and a small temperature change. Even with these cues, reproduction does not occur every year for the Alabama Cavefish. Years that reproduction does occur, only a few eggs are produced per female. It is hypothesized that, because of the jugular position of the vent and the size of the [[Fish anatomy|branchial chamber]], the Alabama Cavefish practices [[Mouthbrooder|branchial incubation]].\n\n== Listing History ==\n\n=== Endangered Species Act ===\nThe Alabama Cavefish was first listed as a threatened species under the Endangered Species Act in 1977. Following further assessment of the species\u2019 range and changing environmental conditions, the cavefish was considered an endangered species in 1988. By 1990, a recovery plan was created for the fish, which stipulates that the species would be down-listed when the following three criteria are met: (1) three other viable populations are found in discontinuous aquatic systems outside the Key Cave area, (2) the aquifer recharge areas for all four populations are protected, and (3) all four populations are demonstrated to be stable or increasing over at least a 20-year period.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ecos.fws.gov/docs/recovery_plan/901025.pdf|title=Alabama Cavefish Recovery Plan|last=|first=|date=1990|website=U.S Fish & Wildlife Service Environmental Conservation Online System|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, amendments to the recovery plan were created that changed the criteria for down-listing and created a criterion for delisting. In order to be delisted, the criteria now stipulate that: (1) the species must demonstrate a stable or increasing trend in the existing Key Cave population, (2) two more cavefish populations must be created, and (3) the aquifer recharge areas must be delineated, mapped, and protected. In order for the cavefish to be delisted entirely, the aquifer recharge area must be protected by a conservation mechanism for at least one of the new populations and all other threats to the cavefish must be addressed or managed, allowing viability for the foreseeable future.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ecos.fws.gov/docs/recovery_plan/Alabama%20Cavefish%20Recovery%20Plan%20Amendment.pdf|title=Recovery Plan for the Alabama Cavefish|last=|first=|date=2019|website=U.S. Fish & Wildlife Service Environmental Conservation Online System|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== International Union for Conservation of Nature Red List ===\nThe Alabama Cavefish was first listed on the IUCN Red List of Threatened Species in 1986 as vulnerable and remained in that category following re-evaluation in 1988. Two years later, the status of the cavefish was reassessed and upgraded to endangered, which was then confirmed by a reassessment in 1994. In 1996, the Alabama Cavefish was again upgraded to critically endangered due to their lack of extent (100 sq. km), low population size, and numerous habitat challenges. The species was last assessed in April of 2012, and although its population trend is stable, it is still listed as critically endangered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/en|title=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species: Speoplatyrhinus poulsoni|last=Authority)|first=NatureServe (Red List Partner & Red List|date=2012-04-12|website=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Conservation ==\nThere are a few current conservation measures put in place to protect the Alabama cavefish. Along with being listed under the ESA, the species is protected by the [[Lacey Act of 1900|Lacey Act]]. This makes it unlawful to import, export, transport, sell, receive, acquire, or purchase (alive or dead including parts, products, eggs, or offspring) the Alabama Cavefish. Secondly, The Tennessee Valley Authority, which owns the two entrances to the caves, have installed a fence to limit human disturbance.<ref name=\":0\" /> Lastly, in 1997, the Key Cave National Wildlife Refuge (NWR) was established. The Key Cave NWR aims at ensuring the biological integrity of the cave through protection of sinkholes that carry surface water directly into the aquifer of the cave.<ref name=\":1\">Bernard R. Kuhajda, email message to author, March 19, 2020.</ref>\u00a0 \n\n== Human Impact ==\nThe largest human-induced threat to the survival of the Alabama Cavefish is groundwater contamination within the recharge area of Key Cave. The recharge area is the place where water seeps into the ground and refills the aquifer. A major source of contamination is the chemicals used to cultivate crops grown in the areas surrounding the cave. Furthermore, collection of the species by amateurs or for scientific purposes pose such a major threat due to the already small population size.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Factors Likely to Cause Extinction ==\nMany factors that are likely to cause the extinction of the Alabama Cavefish are associated with the recharge zone of the Key Cave. The degradation of the groundwater due to agrochemicals and the decreasing level of groundwater limit the entry and cycling of uncontaminated water into Key Cave.<ref name=\":0\" /> Additionally, the alteration of flood cycles within the aquifer often lead to unsuccessful cavefish reproduction.<ref name=\":1\" /> Furthermore, the [[Gray bat]], Myotis grisescens, which is also protected under the ESA, provides nutrients to the Alabama Cavefish through their guano. Therefore, the threats to this bat species also impact the Alabama Cavefish and their fuel source.<ref name=\":0\" /> All these factors combined with the already small population size and limited home range pose massive threats to the Alabama Cavefish.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=33em}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3061096}}\n\n[[Category:Amblyopsidae]]\n[[Category:Cave fish]]\n[[Category:Critically endangered fauna of the United States]]\n[[Category:Freshwater fish of the Southeastern United States|Cavefish, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of Alabama]]\n[[Category:Fish described in 1974]]\n[[Category:ESA endangered species]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Alabama cavefish\n| status = CR\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{Cite iucn | author = NatureServe | title = ''Speoplatyrhinus poulsoni'' | volume = 2013 | page = e.T20467A19033986 | date = 2013 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2013-1.RLTS.T20467A19033986.en }} Listed as Critically Endangered (CR B1ab(iii)+2ab(iii) v3.1)</ref>\n| image = AlabamaCavefish.jpg\n| genus = Speoplatyrhinus\n| parent_authority = [[John Edward Cooper|J. E. Cooper]] & [[Robert Andrew Kuehne|Kuehne]], 1974\n| species = poulsoni\n| authority = J. E. Cooper & Kuehne, 1974<ref>{{ITIS |id=164397|taxon=''Speoplatyrhinus poulsoni''|accessdate=18 April 2006}}</ref>\n| range_map = File:Alabama Cavefish Range.png\n| range_map_caption = The range map of the Alabama Cavefish.\n}}\n\nThe '''Alabama cavefish''' (''Speoplatyrhinus poulsoni''), is a [[critically endangered]] species of [[Amblyopsidae|amblyopsid cavefish]] found only in underground pools in Key Cave, located in northwestern [[Alabama]], United States in the [[Key Cave National Wildlife Refuge]].<ref name=\"Fishbase\">{{FishBase species |genus=Speoplatyrhinus|species=poulsoni|month= March|year=2006}}</ref> It was discovered underneath a colony of [[gray bat]]s in 1967 by researchers Robert A. Kuehne and John E. Cooper<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Romero|first=Aldemaro|date=1998|title=Threatened fishes of the world: Speoplatyrhinus poulsoni|url=http://link.springer.com/10.1023/A:1007405815580|journal=Environmental Biology of Fishes|volume=53|issue=3|pages=293\u2013294|doi=10.1023/A:1007405815580|via=}}</ref> and [[Species description|scientifically described]] in 1974.<ref name=Cooper1974>Cooper, J.E., and R.A. Kuehne (1974). \"Speoplatyrhinus poulsoni, a New Genus and Species of Subterranean Fish from Alabama.\" Copeia 1974: 486-93.</ref>\n\nOn any single visit to the cave, no more than 10 individuals of this fish have been observed, and scientists estimate fewer than 100 are left.<ref name=iucn/> This fish is believed to be the rarest species of [[cavefish]] in the United States and one of the rarest of all freshwater fish. It exists in a fragile ecosystem based on nutrient-rich [[guano]] of the gray bat.<ref name=\"fws\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fws.gov/ecos/ajax/docs/life_histories/E011.html|title=Alabama Cavefish|publisher=U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007234105/http://www.fws.gov/ecos/ajax/docs/life_histories/E011.html|archivedate=7 October 2014|accessdate=12 October 2011}}</ref> Researchers have failed to find the fish in any other location.<ref name=iucn/>\n\nThe only species in its genus, the Alabama cavefish is in danger of extinction. Conservation measures that have been taken to save the species from extinction include protecting the fish under the [[Lacey Act of 1900|Lacey Act]] and limiting human disturbance of Key Cave.\n\n==Habitat and Distribution==\n\nThe Alabama cavefish is one of the rarest [[cavefish]] species in North America. While the specific habitat requirements of the fish are unknown, it is known that the Alabama cavefish is a cave obligate, restricted to [[Key Cave National Wildlife Refuge|Key Cave]] in [[Lauderdale County, Alabama]]. Cave habitats tend to be stable, with drastic changes mainly being associated with the inflow of water. Annual rainfall and flooding in the cave produce changes in water level, temperature, and food availability for the fish. Researchers speculate that the flooding may trigger a hormonal change in the cavefish for growth and reproduction.\n\nSince the discovery of the cavefish, only 9 specimens have been collected (all before 1983). Because very few individuals have been collected and observed and the population is confined to [[Key Cave National Wildlife Refuge|Key Cave]]'','' the Alabama cavefish may be the rarest of the American cavefish and the rarest freshwater fish.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Romero|first=Aldemaro|date=1998|title=Threatened fishes of the world: Speoplatyrhinus poulsoni|url=http://link.springer.com/10.1023/A:1007405815580|journal=Environmental Biology of Fishes|volume=53|issue=3|pages=293\u2013294|doi=10.1023/A:1007405815580|via=}}</ref> \n\nBecause the underground water system in the area is so widespread, it was hoped that the cavefish had dispersed to other sites. However, studies of 120 other caves in the area, conducted since 1977, have failed to locate any other cavefish populations. No more than 10 individuals have been observed on any single visit to the Key Cave and in 36 visits from 1967 to 1998, the average was less than 4 per visit.<ref name=\"iucn\" /> The total number of individuals in the Key Cave population is estimated to be less than 100.<ref name=\"iucn\" /> Initially classified as [[Vulnerable species|vulnerable]] by the [[IUCN]], its status has been gradually upgraded as its extreme rarity became apparent. It is currently considered [[critically endangered]].<ref name=\"iucn\" /> Two reports of these fish in nearby Collier Cave are unconfirmed. Both caves are protected and inaccessible to the public.\n\nBecause its known range is limited to a single cave, the Alabama cavefish has an uncertain future, being threatened by changes in groundwater quality and level, changes in [[aquifer]] characteristics, and diminished organic input. It also may compete with the syntopic [[southern cavefish]] (''Typhlichthys subterraneus''), which is more abundant and aggressive.<ref name=\"fws\" /> Cave crayfish sometimes feed on Alabama cavefish.<ref name=\"fws\" />\n\n==Physiology==\n\nThe Alabama cavefish is up to {{convert|7.2|cm|in|abbr=on}} long and has no eyes or discernible pigmentation,<ref name=\"Fishbase\"/> appearing semitransparent with a slight pink hue. Its large head makes up more than one-third of its length. It is the only species in its genus, and can be distinguished from other cavefish with its very elongated, flattened head with a laterally constricted snout and a terminal mouth. The cavefish lacks pelvic fins, and its fin rays are unbranched with the fin membranes deeply incised between the rays. It has an elaborate system of sensory papillae, arranged in ridges on the head and sides, an adaptation to the dark environment.<ref name=\"fws\"/> The Alabama cavefish has the most highly developed caudal sensory papillae in the Amblyopsidae family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ecos.fws.gov/ecp0/profile/speciesProfile?sId=50|title=Species Profile|website=ecos.fws.gov|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==Diet==\n\nIts diet of [[copepod]]s, [[isopod]]s, [[amphipod]]s, and smaller cavefish is supported by the nutrient-filled bat guano.<ref name=\"fws\"/> It can also survive on other small organisms such as mites, spiders, millipedes, and beetles and other insects.<ref name=\"Outdoor Alabama\">{{cite web|url=http://www.outdooralabama.com/fishing/freshwater/fish/other/cavefish/alabama/|title=Alabama Cavefish|accessdate=9 March 2009|year=2008|publisher=Outdoor Alabama|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090316212948/http://www.outdooralabama.com/fishing/freshwater/fish/other/cavefish/alabama/|archivedate=16 March 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Reproduction==\n\nThere is little information available on the reproductive cycle of the Alabama cavefish. Some speculate that it may reproduce like the [[northern cavefish]] by carrying its young [[Mouthbrooder|inside its mouth]] to be incubated.<ref name=\"Outdoor Alabama\"/> The Alabama cavefish, like most fish, utilizes seasonal cues to trigger hormonal changes that lead to its growth and reproduction. While most fish rely on a large change in water temperature or photoperiod, the Alabama cavefish rely on flooding of the cave in the winter and spring.'''<ref name=\"fws\" />''' This results in an increase in flow of water into the cave and a small temperature change. Even with these cues, reproduction does not occur every year for the Alabama Cavefish. Years that reproduction does occur, only a few eggs are produced per female. It is hypothesized that, because of the jugular position of the vent and the size of the [[Fish anatomy|branchial chamber]], the Alabama Cavefish practices [[Mouthbrooder|branchial incubation]].\n\n== Status and Conservation ==\n\n=== Listing History ===\n\n==== Endangered Species Act ====\nThe Alabama Cavefish was first listed as a threatened species under the Endangered Species Act in 1977. Following further assessment of the species\u2019 range and changing environmental conditions, the cavefish was considered an endangered species in 1988. By 1990, a recovery plan was created for the fish, which stipulates that the species would be down-listed when the following three criteria are met: (1) three other viable populations are found in discontinuous aquatic systems outside the Key Cave area, (2) the aquifer recharge areas for all four populations are protected, and (3) all four populations are demonstrated to be stable or increasing over at least a 20-year period.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ecos.fws.gov/docs/recovery_plan/901025.pdf|title=Alabama Cavefish Recovery Plan|last=|first=|date=1990|website=U.S Fish & Wildlife Service Environmental Conservation Online System|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, amendments to the recovery plan were created that changed the criteria for down-listing and created a criterion for delisting. In order to be delisted, the criteria now stipulate that: (1) the species must demonstrate a stable or increasing trend in the existing Key Cave population, (2) two more cavefish populations must be created, and (3) the aquifer recharge areas must be delineated, mapped, and protected. In order for the cavefish to be delisted entirely, the aquifer recharge area must be protected by a conservation mechanism for at least one of the new populations and all other threats to the cavefish must be addressed or managed, allowing viability for the foreseeable future.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ecos.fws.gov/docs/recovery_plan/Alabama%20Cavefish%20Recovery%20Plan%20Amendment.pdf|title=Recovery Plan for the Alabama Cavefish|last=|first=|date=2019|website=U.S. Fish & Wildlife Service Environmental Conservation Online System|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==== International Union for Conservation of Nature Red List ====\nThe Alabama Cavefish was first listed on the IUCN Red List of Threatened Species in 1986 as vulnerable and remained in that category following re-evaluation in 1988. Two years later, the status of the cavefish was reassessed and upgraded to endangered, which was then confirmed by a reassessment in 1994. In 1996, the Alabama Cavefish was again upgraded to critically endangered due to their lack of extent (100 sq. km), low population size, and numerous habitat challenges. The species was last assessed in April of 2012, and although its population trend is stable, it is still listed as critically endangered.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/en|title=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species: Speoplatyrhinus poulsoni|last=Authority)|first=NatureServe (Red List Partner & Red List|date=2012-04-12|website=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> \n\n==== Conservation ====\nThere are a few current conservation measures put in place to protect the Alabama cavefish. Along with being listed under the ESA, the species is protected by the [[Lacey Act of 1900|Lacey Act]]. This makes it unlawful to import, export, transport, sell, receive, acquire, or purchase (alive or dead including parts, products, eggs, or offspring) the Alabama Cavefish. Secondly, The Tennessee Valley Authority, which owns the two entrances to the caves, have installed a fence to limit human disturbance.<ref name=\":0\" /> Lastly, in 1997, the Key Cave National Wildlife Refuge (NWR) was established. The Key Cave NWR aims at ensuring the biological integrity of the cave through protection of sinkholes that carry surface water directly into the aquifer of the cave.<ref name=\":1\">Bernard R. Kuhajda, email message to author, March 19, 2020.</ref>\u00a0 \n\n== Human Impact ==\nThe largest human-induced threat to the survival of the Alabama Cavefish is groundwater contamination within the recharge area of Key Cave. The recharge area is the place where water seeps into the ground and refills the aquifer. A major source of contamination is the chemicals used to cultivate crops grown in the areas surrounding the cave. Furthermore, collection of the species by amateurs or for scientific purposes pose such a major threat due to the already small population size.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Factors Likely to Cause Extinction ==\nMany factors that are likely to cause the extinction of the Alabama Cavefish are associated with the recharge zone of the Key Cave. The degradation of the groundwater due to agrochemicals and the decreasing level of groundwater limit the entry and cycling of uncontaminated water into Key Cave.<ref name=\":0\" /> Additionally, the alteration of flood cycles within the aquifer often lead to unsuccessful cavefish reproduction.<ref name=\":1\" /> Furthermore, the [[Gray bat]], Myotis grisescens, which is also protected under the ESA, provides nutrients to the Alabama Cavefish through their guano. Therefore, the threats to this bat species also impact the Alabama Cavefish and their fuel source.<ref name=\":0\" /> All these factors combined with the already small population size and limited home range pose massive threats to the Alabama Cavefish.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=33em}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3061096}}\n\n[[Category:Amblyopsidae]]\n[[Category:Cave fish]]\n[[Category:Critically endangered fauna of the United States]]\n[[Category:Freshwater fish of the Southeastern United States|Cavefish, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of Alabama]]\n[[Category:Fish described in 1974]]\n[[Category:ESA endangered species]]\n", "name_user": "Jrhabib29", "label": "safe", "comment": "I split the Status and Conservation section in two.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alabama_cavefish"}
{"title_page": "Sergio Lagan\u00e0", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Sergio Lagan\u00e0\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| fullname       =\n| nickname       =\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1982|11|4|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Reggio Calabria]], Italy\n| height         =\n| weight         =\n| currentteam    = Retired\n| discipline     = Road\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      =\n| amateuryears1  =\n| amateurteam1   =\n| amateuryears2  =\n| amateurteam2   =\n| proyears1      = 2007\n| proteam1       = {{ct|TEN|2007}}\n| proyears2      = 2008\u20132009\n| proteam2       = {{ct|LPR|2008}}\n| proyears3      = 2010\u20132012\n| proteam3       = {{ct|UNA|2010}}\n| majorwins      =\n| medaltemplates =\n| show-medals    =\n}}\n\n'''Sergio Lagan\u00e0''' (born 4 November 1982) is an Italian former professional [[road cyclist]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/rider.php?id=135406 | title=Sergio Lagana | work=ProCyclingStats | accessdate=13 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Major results==\n;2008\n: 1st Stage 2 [[Tour Ivoirien de la Paix]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Cycling Archives|30025|Sergio Lagan\u00e0}}\n*{{CQ Ranking|m|7105|Sergio Lagana}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lagana, Sergio}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from Reggio Calabria]]\n\n\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1980s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Sergio Lagan\u00e0\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| fullname       =\n| nickname       =\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1982|11|4|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Reggio Calabria]], Italy\n| height         =\n| weight         =\n| currentteam    = Retired\n| discipline     = Road\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      =\n| amateuryears1  =\n| amateurteam1   =\n| amateuryears2  =\n| amateurte