{"title_page": "Siliput language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Siliput\n|nativename=''Maimai''\n|states=[[Papua New Guinea]]\n|region=[[Sandaun Province]]\n|coordinates={{coord|-3.632449|142.434278|type:city_region:PG|name=Seleput}}\n|speakers=520\n|date=2003\n|ref=e18\n|familycolor=Papuan\n|fam1=[[Torricelli languages|Torricelli]]\n|fam2=[[Maimai languages|Maimai]]\n|fam3=Maimai proper\n|iso3=mkc\n|glotto=sili1247\n|glottorefname=Siliput\n}}\n\n'''Siliput''', a.k.a. '''Maimai''', is a [[Torricelli languages|Torricelli language]] of [[Papua New Guinea]]. It is spoken in Seleput village ({{coord|-3.632449|142.434278|type:city_region:PG|name=Seleput}}), [[Mawase Rural LLG]], [[Sandaun Province]].<ref name=\"Ethnologue22-PNG\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ethnologue.com/country/PG/languages |title=Papua New Guinea languages |work=[[Ethnologue]]: Languages of the World |edition=22nd |editor1-last=Eberhard |editor1-first=David M. |editor2-last=Simons |editor2-first=Gary F. |editor3-last=Fennig |editor3-first=Charles D. |date=2019 |location=Dallas |publisher=[[SIL International]]}}</ref><ref name=\"UN-PNG\">{{cite web |url=https://data.humdata.org/dataset/village-coordinates-lookup |title=Papua New Guinea Village Coordinates Lookup |author=United Nations in Papua New Guinea |work=Humanitarian Data Exchange |version=1.31.9 |date=2018}}</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n* [[Paradisec]] has [http://catalog.paradisec.org.au/collections/search?language_code=mkc a number of collections that include Siliput language materials.]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Torricelli languages}}\n{{Languages of Papua New Guinea}}\n\n[[Category:Maimai languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Papua New Guinea]]\n[[Category:Languages of Sandaun Province]]\n\n\n{{papuan-lang-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Siliput\n|nativename=Maimai\n|states=[[Papua New Guinea]]\n|region=[[Sandaun Province]]\n|coordinates={{coord|-3.632449|142.434278|type:city_region:PG|name=Seleput}}\n|speakers=520\n|date=2003\n|ref=e18\n|familycolor=Papuan\n|fam1=[[Torricelli languages|Torricelli]]\n|fam2=[[Maimai languages|Maimai]]\n|fam3=Maimai proper\n|iso3=mkc\n|glotto=sili1247\n|glottorefname=Siliput\n}}\n\n'''Siliput''', a.k.a. '''Maimai''', is a [[Torricelli languages|Torricelli language]] of [[Papua New Guinea]]. It is spoken in Seleput village ({{coord|-3.632449|142.434278|type:city_region:PG|name=Seleput}}), [[Mawase Rural LLG]], [[Sandaun Province]].<ref name=\"Ethnologue22-PNG\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ethnologue.com/country/PG/languages |title=Papua New Guinea languages |work=[[Ethnologue]]: Languages of the World |edition=22nd |editor1-last=Eberhard |editor1-first=David M. |editor2-last=Simons |editor2-first=Gary F. |editor3-last=Fennig |editor3-first=Charles D. |date=2019 |location=Dallas |publisher=[[SIL International]]}}</ref><ref name=\"UN-PNG\">{{cite web |url=https://data.humdata.org/dataset/village-coordinates-lookup |title=Papua New Guinea Village Coordinates Lookup |author=United Nations in Papua New Guinea |work=Humanitarian Data Exchange |version=1.31.9 |date=2018}}</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n* [[Paradisec]] has [http://catalog.paradisec.org.au/collections/search?language_code=mkc a number of collections that include Siliput language materials.]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Torricelli languages}}\n{{Languages of Papua New Guinea}}\n\n[[Category:Maimai languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Papua New Guinea]]\n[[Category:Languages of Sandaun Province]]\n\n\n{{papuan-lang-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Liggliluff", "label": "safe", "comment": "nativename in cursive", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siliput_language"}
{"title_page": "Sergio Ghisalberti", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name        = Sergio Ghisalberti\n| image       =\n| fullname    = Sergio Ghisalberti\n| nickname    =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1979|12|10}}\n| birth_place = [[San Giovanni Bianco]], [[Italy]]\n| height      =\n| weight      =\n| currentteam =\n| discipline  = Road\n| role        = Rider\n| ridertype   =\n| proyears1   = 2005\n| proteam1    = Domina Vacanze\n| proyears2   = 2006&ndash;2008\n| proteam2    = Milram\n| majorwins   =\n}}\n\n'''Sergio Ghisalberti''' (born 10 December 1979 in [[San Giovanni Bianco]]) is an [[Italy|Italian]] professional [[road bicycle racer]].\n\n== Palmares ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Vuelta a Burgos]] - Mountains Competition (2006)\n* [[Giro di Lombardia]] - U23 version (2003)\n{{div col end}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{trapfriis|italy.Ghisalberti.htm}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ghisalberti, Sergio}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Bergamo]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lombardy]]\n[[Category:Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a cyclists]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n\n\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1970s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name        = Sergio Ghisalberti\n| image       =\n| fullname    = Sergio Ghisalberti\n| nickname    =\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1979|12|10}}\n| birth_place = [[San Giovanni Bianco]], [[Italy]]\n| height      =\n| weight      =\n| currentteam =\n| discipline  = Road\n| role        = Rider\n| ridertype   =\n| proyears1   = 2005\n| proteam1    = Domina Vacanze\n| proyears2   = 2006&ndash;2008\n| proteam2    = Milram\n| majorwins   =\n}}\n\n'''Sergio Ghisalberti''' (born 10 December 1979 in [[San Giovanni Bianco]]) is an [[Italy|Italian]] professional [[road bicycle racer]].\n\n== Palmares ==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Vuelta a Burgos]] - Mountains Competition (2006)\n* [[Giro di Lombardia]] - U23 version (2003)\n{{div col end}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{trapfriis|italy.Ghisalberti.htm}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ghisalberti, Sergio}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Bergamo]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Lombardy]]\n[[Category:Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a cyclists]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n\n\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1970s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sergio_Ghisalberti"}
{"title_page": "View from the House", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = View from the House\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Kim Carnes]]\n| cover      = ViewFromTheHouse.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = July 25, 1988\n| recorded   = 1988 at Sound Stage Studio, Emerald Sound Studios and Manzanita Recording Studio, [[Nashville, Tennessee]]; [[Galaxy Studios]], [[Hollywood]], [[California]].\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]], [[adult contemporary music|adult contemporary]]\n| length     = 38:37\n| label      = [[Music Corporation of America|MCA]]\n| producer   = Kim Carnes and [[Jimmy Bowen]] (\"Crimes of the Heart\" produced by Kim Carnes, [[Jimmy Bowen]] and Bill Cuomo)\n| prev_title = [[Light House (Kim Carnes album)|Light House]]\n| prev_year  = 1986\n| next_title = [[Checkin' Out the Ghosts]]\n| next_year  = 1991\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = View from the House\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Crazy in Love (Kim Carnes song)|Crazy in Love]]\n | single1date = 1988\n | single2     = Speed of the Sound of Loneliness\n | single2date = 1988\n | single3     = Just to Spend Tonight with You\n | single3date = 1988\n | single4     = Fantastic Fire of Love\n | single4date = 1989\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''View from the House''''' is the eleventh studio album by American singer-songwriter [[Kim Carnes]]. It was released on July 25, 1988 by [[Music Corporation of America|MCA Records]]. The album marked a return to her early [[country music]] roots.<ref name=\"KimCarnesBio\">{{cite web|last=Huey|first=Steve|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/view-from-the-house-mw0000196563|title=Kim Carnes biography|publisher=[[AllMusic]]. [[All Media Network]]|accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref> Carnes recorded the album in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], and co-produced the album with [[Jimmy Bowen]].\n\n''View from the House'' received positive reviews, with music critics praising Carnes's cover songs. The album reached number 39 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Top Country Albums chart, and contained two hit singles. \"[[Crazy in Love (Kim Carnes song)|Crazy in Love]]\" and \"Speed of the Sound of Loneliness\" both charted on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Singles & Tracks]] at number 68 and number 70 respectively. \"Crazy in Love\" also reached number 13 on the [[Hot Adult Contemporary Tracks|Adult Contemporary]] chart.\n\n==Background==\nPrior to making the album, Carnes stated, \"I can't do another album here (in Los Angeles). I've tried and finally stopped. The only way I get a thrill out of recording is to record live as opposed to running everything through a computer. I want to feel that interplay between musicians. And I feel real strongly that Nashville is the place to make an album with real instruments.\"<ref>Interview with Kim Carnes. Gettysburg Times, October 3-4, 1987. Retrieved 16 April 2015.</ref>\n\nCarnes had been interested in the Nashville music scene since 1981, after hearing [[Rosanne Cash]]'s album ''[[Seven Year Ache]]''. Carnes wanted to work with [[Jimmy Bowen]], who produced her debut album, ''[[Rest on Me]]'', in 1971.<ref name=\"PopMatters\">{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/where-the-heart-is-an-interview-with-multi-grammy-winner-kim-carnes-part-tw-2495394072.html?rebelltitem=2#rebelltitem2|title=Where the Heart Is An Interview With Multi-Grammy Winner Kim Carnes, Part Two|last=Wikane|first=Christian John|work=[[PopMatters]]|date=April 24, 2017|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nCarnes chose to record a cover of \"If You Don't Want My Love\" by [[John Prine]]. The head of A&R at MCA suggested to Carnes that she also record Prine's song \"Speed of the Sound of Loneliness\". \"Who thinks of that?\" Carnes said. \"The speed of the sound of loneliness? Lyrically, that blew me away.\"<ref name=\"PopMatters\"/>\n\nCarnes wrote \"Blood from the Bandit\", with [[Donna Weiss]], as a reflection on \"pollution, greed, and other conditions afflicting the world\". \"The song is still pertinent today, more so, maybe,\" Carnes said in 2017. \"What was being talked about then is on steroids now.\"<ref name=\"PopMatters\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album reviews\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}} [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=mw0000196563|pure_url=yes}} link]\n}}\nThe album received a positive review from ''[[People magazine]]''. \"Carnes, sounding wonderfully relaxed and justifiably pleased with herself, sails through 10 generally splendid tunes.\" They stated that Carnes's cover of [[John Prine]]'s song \"Speed of the Sound of Loneliness\"\" exploited the song \"affectingly,\" and that her cover of Even Stevens' \"[[Crazy in Love (Kim Carnes song)|Crazy in Love]]\" sounds \"convincingly romantic.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Novak|first1=Ralph|last2=Hiltbrand|first2=David|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20099773,00.html|title=Picks and Pans Review: View from the House|magazine=[[People (American magazine)|People Magazine]]|accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref> ''Allmusic'' retrospectively described the album as \"[a return] to the folk and country music of her earlier years.\"<ref name=\"KimCarnesBio\"/>\n\n==Promotion==\n===Singles===\nFour singles were released from ''View from the House''. The first US single was \"Speed of the Sound of Loneliness\", which charted at number 70 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Songs]] chart.<ref name=\"BillboardHotCountrySongs\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/305869/kim-carnes/chart?f=357|title=Kim Carnes - Chart history - Hot Country Songs|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref> The second single, \"[[Crazy in Love (Kim Carnes song)|Crazy in Love]]\", first recorded by [[Joe Cocker]] in 1984, reached number 68 on the ''Billboard'' Hot Country Songs chart,<ref name=\"BillboardHotCountrySongs\" /> and reached number 13 on the ''Billboard'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/305869/kim-carnes/chart?f=341|title=Kim Carnes - Chart history - Adult Contemporary|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref> The third single, \"Just to Spend Tonight with You\", was released in the United Kingdom, though did not chart. The fourth single, \"Fantastic Fire of Love\", was released in 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.si/books?id=XUI1R7jJz2YC&lpg=PP1&dq=Goldmine%20Standard%20Catalog%20of%20American%20Records%201948-1991&hl=sl&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Goldmine Standard Catalog of American Records 1948\u20131991|accessdate=31 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = {{duration|m=38|s=37}}\n| title1= Brass & Batons\n| writer1 = {{flat list|\n*[[Kim Carnes]]\n*[[Donna Terry Weiss|Donna Weiss]]\n}}\n| extra1 = {{flat list|\n*[[Jimmy Bowen]]\n*Carnes\n}}\n| length1 = 5:19\n\n| title2 = Just to Spend Tonight with You\n| writer2 = {{flat list|\n*Carnes\n*Weiss\n}}\n| extra2 = {{flat list|\n*Bowen\n*Carnes\n}}\n| length2 = 4:48\n\n| title3 = Heartbreak Radio\n| writer3 = {{flat list|\n*[[Troy Seals]]\n*[[Frankie Miller]]\n}}\n| extra3 = {{flat list|\n*Bowen\n*Carnes\n}}\n| length3 = 3:16\n\n| title4 = [[Crazy in Love (Kim Carnes song)|Crazy in Love]]\n| writer4 = {{flat list|\n*Even Stevens\n*Randy McCormick\n}}\n| extra4 = {{flat list|\n*Bowen\n*Carnes\n}}\n| length4 = 3:52\n\n| title5 = If You Don't Want My Love\n| writer5 = {{flat list|\n*[[John Prine]]\n*[[Phil Spector]]\n}}\n| extra5 = {{flat list|\n*Bowen\n*Carnes\n}}\n| length5 = 3:15\n\n| title6 = Willie and the Hand Jive\n| writer6 = [[Johnny Otis]]\n| extra6 = {{flat list|\n*Bowen\n*Carnes\n}}\n| length6 = 4:05\n\n| title7 = [[Speed of the Sound of Loneliness]]\n| writer7 = Prine\n| extra7 = {{flat list|\n*Bowen\n*Carnes\n}}\n| length7 = 3:26\n\n| title8 = Blood from the Bandit\n| writer8 = {{flat list|\n*Carnes\n*Weiss\n}}\n| extra8 = {{flat list|\n*Bowen\n*Carnes\n}}\n| length8 = 3:17\n\n| title9 = Fantastic Fire of Love\n| writer9 = Carnes\n| extra9 = {{flat list|\n*Bowen\n*Carnes\n}}\n| length9 = 4:12\n\n| title10 = Crimes of the Heart\n| writer10 = {{flat list|\n*Carnes\n*Weiss\n}}\n| extra10 = {{flat list|\n*Bowen\n*Carnes\n*Bill Cuomo\n}}\n| length10 = 3:07\n}}\n\n== Charts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1988)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{album chart|Sweden|47|artist=Kim Carnes|album=View from the House|rowheader=true|accessdate=September 8, 2019}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| US [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] [[Billboard charts|Top Country Albums]]<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/305869/kim-carnes/chart?f=320|title=Chart listing for ''View from the House''|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| 36\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Kim Carnes}}\n\n[[Category:1988 albums]]\n[[Category:Kim Carnes albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Jimmy Bowen]]\n[[Category:MCA Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = View from the House\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Kim Carnes]]\n| cover      = ViewFromTheHouse.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = July 25, 1988\n| recorded   = 1988 at Sound Stage Studio, Emerald Sound Studios and Manzanita Recording Studio, [[Nashville, Tennessee]]; [[Galaxy Studios]], [[Hollywood]], [[California]].\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]], [[adult contemporary music|adult contemporary]]\n| length     = 38:37\n| label      = [[Music Corporation of America|MCA]]\n| producer   = Kim Carnes & [[Jimmy Bowen]] (\"Crimes of the Heart\" produced by Kim Carnes, [[Jimmy Bowen]] and Bill Cuomo)\n| prev_title = [[Light House (Kim Carnes album)|Light House]]\n| prev_year  = 1986\n| next_title = [[Checkin' Out the Ghosts]]\n| next_year  = 1991\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = View from the House\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Crazy in Love (Kim Carnes song)|Crazy in Love]]\n | single1date = 1988\n | single2     = Speed of the Sound of Loneliness\n | single2date = 1988\n | single3     = Just to Spend Tonight with You\n | single3date = 1988\n | single4     = Fantastic Fire of Love\n | single4date = 1989\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''View from the House''''' is the eleventh studio album by American singer-songwriter [[Kim Carnes]]. It was released on July 25, 1988 by [[Music Corporation of America|MCA Records]]. The album marked a return to her early [[country music]] roots.<ref name=\"KimCarnesBio\">{{cite web|last=Huey|first=Steve|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/view-from-the-house-mw0000196563|title=Kim Carnes biography|publisher=[[AllMusic]]. [[All Media Network]]|accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref> Carnes recorded the album in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], and co-produced the album with [[Jimmy Bowen]].\n\n''View from the House'' received positive reviews, with music critics praising Carnes's cover songs. The album reached number 39 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Top Country Albums chart, and contained two hit singles. \"[[Crazy in Love (Kim Carnes song)|Crazy in Love]]\" and \"Speed of the Sound of Loneliness\" both charted on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Singles & Tracks]] at number 68 and number 70 respectively. \"Crazy in Love\" also reached number 13 on the [[Hot Adult Contemporary Tracks|Adult Contemporary]] chart.\n\n==Background==\nPrior to making the album, Carnes stated, \"I can't do another album here (in Los Angeles). I've tried and finally stopped. The only way I get a thrill out of recording is to record live as opposed to running everything through a computer. I want to feel that interplay between musicians. And I feel real strongly that Nashville is the place to make an album with real instruments.\"<ref>Interview with Kim Carnes. Gettysburg Times, October 3-4, 1987. Retrieved 16 April 2015.</ref>\n\nCarnes had been interested in the Nashville music scene since 1981, after hearing [[Rosanne Cash]]'s album ''[[Seven Year Ache]]''. Carnes wanted to work with [[Jimmy Bowen]], who produced her debut album, ''[[Rest on Me]]'', in 1971.<ref name=\"PopMatters\">{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/where-the-heart-is-an-interview-with-multi-grammy-winner-kim-carnes-part-tw-2495394072.html?rebelltitem=2#rebelltitem2|title=Where the Heart Is An Interview With Multi-Grammy Winner Kim Carnes, Part Two|last=Wikane|first=Christian John|work=[[PopMatters]]|date=April 24, 2017|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\nCarnes chose to record a cover of \"If You Don't Want My Love\" by [[John Prine]]. The head of A&R at MCA suggested to Carnes that she also record Prine's song \"Speed of the Sound of Loneliness\". \"Who thinks of that?\" Carnes said. \"The speed of the sound of loneliness? Lyrically, that blew me away.\"<ref name=\"PopMatters\"/>\n\nCarnes wrote \"Blood from the Bandit\", with [[Donna Weiss]], as a reflection on \"pollution, greed, and other conditions afflicting the world\". \"The song is still pertinent today, more so, maybe,\" Carnes said in 2017. \"What was being talked about then is on steroids now.\"<ref name=\"PopMatters\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album reviews\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}} [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=mw0000196563|pure_url=yes}} link]\n}}\nThe album received a positive review from ''[[People magazine]]''. \"Carnes, sounding wonderfully relaxed and justifiably pleased with herself, sails through 10 generally splendid tunes.\" They stated that Carnes's cover of [[John Prine]]'s song \"Speed of the Sound of Loneliness\"\" exploited the song \"affectingly,\" and that her cover of Even Stevens' \"[[Crazy in Love (Kim Carnes song)|Crazy in Love]]\" sounds \"convincingly romantic.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Novak|first1=Ralph|last2=Hiltbrand|first2=David|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20099773,00.html|title=Picks and Pans Review: View from the House|magazine=[[People (American magazine)|People Magazine]]|accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref> ''Allmusic'' retrospectively described the album as \"[a return] to the folk and country music of her earlier years.\"<ref name=\"KimCarnesBio\"/>\n\n==Promotion==\n===Singles===\nFour singles were released from ''View from the House''. The first US single was \"Speed of the Sound of Loneliness\", which charted at number 70 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Songs]] chart.<ref name=\"BillboardHotCountrySongs\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/305869/kim-carnes/chart?f=357|title=Kim Carnes - Chart history - Hot Country Songs|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref> The second single, \"[[Crazy in Love (Kim Carnes song)|Crazy in Love]]\", first recorded by [[Joe Cocker]] in 1984, reached number 68 on the ''Billboard'' Hot Country Songs chart,<ref name=\"BillboardHotCountrySongs\" /> and reached number 13 on the ''Billboard'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/305869/kim-carnes/chart?f=341|title=Kim Carnes - Chart history - Adult Contemporary|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref> The third single, \"Just to Spend Tonight with You\", was released in the United Kingdom, though did not chart. The fourth single, \"Fantastic Fire of Love\", was released in 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.si/books?id=XUI1R7jJz2YC&lpg=PP1&dq=Goldmine%20Standard%20Catalog%20of%20American%20Records%201948-1991&hl=sl&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Goldmine Standard Catalog of American Records 1948\u20131991|accessdate=31 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = {{duration|m=38|s=37}}\n| title1= Brass & Batons\n| writer1 = {{flat list|\n*[[Kim Carnes]]\n*[[Donna Terry Weiss|Donna Weiss]]\n}}\n| extra1 = {{flat list|\n*[[Jimmy Bowen]]\n*Carnes\n}}\n| length1 = 5:19\n\n| title2 = Just to Spend Tonight with You\n| writer2 = {{flat list|\n*Carnes\n*Weiss\n}}\n| extra2 = {{flat list|\n*Bowen\n*Carnes\n}}\n| length2 = 4:48\n\n| title3 = Heartbreak Radio\n| writer3 = {{flat list|\n*[[Troy Seals]]\n*[[Frankie Miller]]\n}}\n| extra3 = {{flat list|\n*Bowen\n*Carnes\n}}\n| length3 = 3:16\n\n| title4 = [[Crazy in Love (Kim Carnes song)|Crazy in Love]]\n| writer4 = {{flat list|\n*Even Stevens\n*Randy McCormick\n}}\n| extra4 = {{flat list|\n*Bowen\n*Carnes\n}}\n| length4 = 3:52\n\n| title5 = If You Don't Want My Love\n| writer5 = {{flat list|\n*[[John Prine]]\n*[[Phil Spector]]\n}}\n| extra5 = {{flat list|\n*Bowen\n*Carnes\n}}\n| length5 = 3:15\n\n| title6 = Willie and the Hand Jive\n| writer6 = [[Johnny Otis]]\n| extra6 = {{flat list|\n*Bowen\n*Carnes\n}}\n| length6 = 4:05\n\n| title7 = [[Speed of the Sound of Loneliness]]\n| writer7 = Prine\n| extra7 = {{flat list|\n*Bowen\n*Carnes\n}}\n| length7 = 3:26\n\n| title8 = Blood from the Bandit\n| writer8 = {{flat list|\n*Carnes\n*Weiss\n}}\n| extra8 = {{flat list|\n*Bowen\n*Carnes\n}}\n| length8 = 3:17\n\n| title9 = Fantastic Fire of Love\n| writer9 = Carnes\n| extra9 = {{flat list|\n*Bowen\n*Carnes\n}}\n| length9 = 4:12\n\n| title10 = Crimes of the Heart\n| writer10 = {{flat list|\n*Carnes\n*Weiss\n}}\n| extra10 = {{flat list|\n*Bowen\n*Carnes\n*Bill Cuomo\n}}\n| length10 = 3:07\n}}\n\n== Charts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1988)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{album chart|Sweden|47|artist=Kim Carnes|album=View from the House|rowheader=true|accessdate=September 8, 2019}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| US [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] [[Billboard charts|Top Country Albums]]<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/305869/kim-carnes/chart?f=320|title=Chart listing for ''View from the House''|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| 36\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Kim Carnes}}\n\n[[Category:1988 albums]]\n[[Category:Kim Carnes albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Jimmy Bowen]]\n[[Category:MCA Records albums]]\n", "name_user": "Joshuadejohnson", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/View_from_the_House"}
{"title_page": "Paschal Triduum", "text_new": "[[File:Meister des Hausbuches 003.jpg|thumb|''Christ Washing the Feet of the Apostles'' by Meister des Hausbuches, 1475 ([[Gem\u00e4ldegalerie]], [[Berlin]])]]\nThe '''Paschal Triduum''' ([[Latin]]: ''Triduum Paschale''),<ref>For the etymology of the term ''Paschal'' see ''[[Names of Easter#From Greek Pascha|Names of Easter]]''.</ref> '''Holy Triduum''' (Latin: ''Triduum Sacrum''), or '''Easter Triduum''', or the '''Three Days''',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elca.org/Growing-In-Faith/Worship/Planning/Three-Days.aspx|title=The Three Days: Maundy Thursday, Good Friday, and the Vigil of Easter|year=2012|publisher=[[Evangelical Lutheran Church in America]]|accessdate=1 April 2012}}</ref> is the period of three days that begins with the liturgy on the evening of [[Maundy Thursday]],<ref name=\"CL Thurs\">[http://www.catholicliturgy.com/index.cfm/FuseAction/documentText/Index/2/SubIndex/38/ContentIndex/324/Start/319 Catholic Liturgy, Holy Thursday Evening Mass of the Lord's Supper]</ref> reaches its high point in the [[Easter Vigil]], and closes with evening prayer on [[Easter Sunday]]. <ref name=General>[http://www.catholicliturgy.com/index.cfm/FuseAction/documentText/Index/2/SubIndex/38/ContentIndex/101/Start/97 General Norms for the Liturgical Year and the Calendar, 19]</ref> It recalls the [[Passion (Christianity)|Passion]], [[Crucifixion of Jesus|Crucifixion]], [[Crucifixion of Jesus|Death]], [[entombment of Christ|burial]], and [[Resurrection of Jesus]], as portrayed in the [[canonical Gospels]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bibleresources.americanbible.org/bible-resources/bible</ref>\n\nIn the [[Anglican]], [[Lutheran]], [[Methodist]], and [[Reformed]] traditions, the Paschal Triduum straddles the two liturgical seasons of [[Lent]] and [[Eastertide|Easter]] in the [[Church calendar]]; however, in the [[Roman Catholic]] tradition, since the [[Pope Pius XII#Liturgy reforms|1955 reform]] by [[Pope Pius XII]], the Easter Triduum has been more clearly distinguished as a separate liturgical period. Previously, all these celebrations were advanced by more than twelve hours. The [[Mass of the Lord's Supper]] and the [[Easter Vigil]] were celebrated in the morning of Thursday and Saturday respectively, and [[Holy Week]] and [[Lent]] were seen as ending only on the approach of Easter.\n\nAfter the [[Gloria in excelsis Deo]] at the Mass of the Lord's Supper, all church bells are silenced and the organ is not used. The period that lasted from Thursday morning to before Easter Sunday began was once, in Anglo-Saxon times, referred to as \"the still days\".<ref>{{CathEncy|wstitle=Holy Week}}</ref>\n\nIn the Catholic Church, [[wedding]]s, which were once prohibited throughout the entire season of Lent and during certain other periods as well,<ref>{{CathEncy|wstitle=Banns of Marriage}}</ref> are prohibited during the Triduum. Lutherans still discourage weddings during the entirety of Holy Week and the Easter Triduum.\n\n==Maundy Thursday (also called Holy Thursday)==\n[[File:Chancel of Houston Memorial UMC on Good Friday.jpg|thumb|350px|On Maundy Thursday, the [[Stripping of the Altar|altar of this Methodist church was stripped]] and the crucifix of this Methodist church was veiled in black for Good Friday (black is the liturgical colour for Good Friday in the United Methodist Church). A wooden cross sits in front of the bare chancel for the veneration of the cross ceremony, which occurs during the United Methodist Good Friday liturgy.]] \n{{Main|Maundy Thursday}}\n{{Liturgical year}}\nIn some Protestant denominations, the Triduum begins with an evening [[service of worship|worship service]] on [[Maundy Thursday]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liturgybytlw.com/Lent/MaunFW.html|title=The Triduum: Maundy Thursday with Footwashing|quote=The Maundy Thursday service is one of endings and beginnings. What was begun on Ash Wednesday is brought to a close here today. What begins today does not end until the resurrection of Easter. It is the ancient Triduum, \"The Three Sacred Days,\" which lead us to Easter: Maundy Thursday, Good Friday, and Holy Saturday.|publisher=[[Evangelical Lutheran Church in America]]|author=Rev. Thomas L. Weitzel|accessdate=1 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Catholic Church]] and in the [[Anglo-Catholic]] tradition of Anglicanism, in the [[Mass of the Lord's Supper]], during the [[Gloria in Excelsis Deo]], all church bells may be rung and the organ played; afterwards, bells and organ are silenced until the Gloria of the Easter Vigil.<ref name=\"CL Thurs\">[http://www.catholicliturgy.com/index.cfm/FuseAction/documentText/Index/2/SubIndex/38/ContentIndex/324/Start/319 Catholic Liturgy, Holy Thursday Evening Mass of the Lord's Supper]</ref> After the [[homily]] or [[sermon]] of the Mass, \"where a pastoral reason suggests it\", a ritual [[washing of the feet]] follows.<ref name=\"CL Thurs\" /><ref>''Roman Missal'', \"Thursday of the Lord's Supper\", 10</ref> The Mass concludes with a procession of the [[Blessed Sacrament]] to the [[altar of repose]].<ref name=\"CL Thurs\" /> In the [[Anglican]] tradition, this is usually followed by the stripping of the altars. [[Eucharistic adoration]] is encouraged after this, but if continued after midnight should be done without outward solemnity.<ref name=\"CL Thurs\" /> In the form of the [[Roman Rite]] in use before 1955, Mass was celebrated in the morning. Some faithful travelled to several churches to pray at each one's Altar of Repose, a practice called [[Seven Churches Visitation]], which now is associated rather with the morning of Good Friday. The Mass included no washing of the feet, which could instead be done in a separate ceremony later in the day. The Mass itself concluded with a ritual [[Stripping of the Altar|stripping]] of all altars except the altar of repose, leaving only the cross and candlesticks. In the present form as revised in 1955, the altar is stripped bare without ceremony at some time after the evening Mass.\n\nThe [[liturgical colour]] for the Mass vestments and other ornaments is white in the Catholic and Anglican Churches.<ref>[http://www.liturgyoffice.org.uk/Resources/GIRM/Documents/GIRM.pdf General Instruction of the Roman Missal, 346]</ref> In the Lutheran Church, the liturgical colour for Maundy Thursday is white.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elca.org/Growing-In-Faith/Worship/Learning-Center/FAQs/Liturgical-Colors.aspx|title=What is the meaning and use of liturgical colors?|publisher=[[Evangelical Lutheran Church in America]]|quote=Maundy Thursday: For this fourth day of Holy Week, celebrated as the institution of the Lord\u2019s Supper, scarlet or white is used.|accessdate=1 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404093828/http://www.elca.org/Growing-In-Faith/Worship/Learning-Center/FAQs/Liturgical-Colors.aspx|archivedate=4 April 2012}}</ref> In the [[Reformed]] tradition, white or gold may be used.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucc.org/worship/liturgies/liturgical-colors.html?print=t|title=Liturgical Colors and the seasons of the church year|publisher=[[United Church of Christ]]|quote=On Maundy Thursday, White or Gold symbolizes the church's rejoicing in the sacrament of the Lord's Supper. But at the end of the Maundy Thursday celebration, the mood changes abruptly: all decorations are removed and the Holy Table is stripped bare. The church becomes as empty as a tomb. On Good Friday, either Black or Red is customary\u2014although the use of no color at all is also appropriate.|accessdate=1 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427221700/http://www.ucc.org/worship/liturgies/liturgical-colors.html?print=t|archivedate=27 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Good Friday==\n[[File:Ecce homo by Antonio Ciseri (1).jpg|thumb|''[[Ecce Homo]]'' by [[Antonio Ciseri]] (19th century).]]\n{{Main|Good Friday}}\n\nOn Good Friday, Christians recall the [[Passion (Christianity)|passion]] and crucifixion of Jesus.\n\nIn the Roman Catholic, Lutheran, and Anglo-Catholic rites, a cross or crucifix (not necessarily the one that stands on or near the altar on other days of the year) is ceremonially unveiled.<ref>{{CathEncy|wstitle=Good Friday}}</ref> (In pre-1955 services, other crucifixes were to be unveiled, without ceremony, after the Good Friday service.)  In the Catholic ritual, [[clergy]] traditionally begin the service [[prostration|prostrate]] in front of the altar. Mass is not celebrated on Good Friday and the communion distributed at the Celebration of the Lord's Passion is consecrated on Holy Thursday, hence the pre-1955 name \"Mass of the Presanctified\". In Anglican churches, there is no prayer of consecration on Good Friday, and the Reserved Sacrament is distributed at services on that day.  Also in Catholicism, images of saints may, in accordance with local custom, be veiled throughout the last two weeks of Lent. Votive lights before these images are not lit. Crucifixes that are movable are hidden, while those that are not movable are veiled until after the Good Friday service.<ref name=veiling>[http://www.ewtn.com/library/liturgy/zlitur72.htm Covering of Crosses and Images in Lent]</ref> Catholic faithful typically venerate the crucifix by kissing the feet of the corpus. Veneration of a simple wooden cross is common in Anglican worship, with the faithful touching or kissing it.\n\nColors of vestments (and hangings, if kept) vary: no color, red, or black are used in different traditions. The Catholic Church uses red vestments, symbolic of the blood of Jesus Christ, but in the pre-1970 form of the [[Roman Missal]] the priest wears black, changing to violet for the communion part of the service. In Anglican services, [[black vestments]] are sometimes used. In [[The United Methodist Church]], black is the liturgical colour used on Good Friday.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=do7TAAAAMAAJ&q=liturgical+colors+Good+Friday+United+Methodist+Methodist&dq=liturgical+colors+Good+Friday+United+Methodist+Methodist&hl=en&sa=X&ei=agl6T-qZNcbc0QHTltmZDQ&ved=0CGQQ6AEwBg|title=Christian Advocate, Volume 5|publisher=[[The United Methodist Church]]|year=1961|quote=The liturgical color for the Lenten season is violet or purple, except for Good Friday when black is used.|accessdate=1 April 2012}}</ref>  In the [[Lutheran]] churches, there is no liturgical color on Good Friday.  Altars remain stripped and clergy wear no vestments on this day.\n\n==Holy Saturday==\n[[File:Resurrection.JPG|thumb|250px|''Jesus Resurrected'' by [[Piero della Francesca]] (15th century).]] \n\nAlso called Black Saturday, is a vigil service that is held after nightfall on Holy Saturday, or before dawn on Easter Sunday, in commemoration Jesus' death and [[harrowing of Hell]]. Many of the details that follow hold for Anglican and Evangelical Lutheran churches as well as Catholic worship.  The ceremony of darkness and light is held at the beginning of the [[Easter Vigil]] Mass. The [[paschal candle]], whose lighting symbolizes the resurrection of Christ from the dead,<ref>[http://www.elca.org/Growing-In-Faith/Worship/Learning-Center/FAQs/Paschal-Candle.aspx How do we use a paschal candle]</ref> is lit from the new Easter fire. The solemn procession to the altar with the Paschal candle is formed. Once everyone has processed in, the [[Exsultet]] is intoned.\n\nAfter the Exsultet, everyone is seated and listens to seven readings from the [[Old Testament]] and seven [[Psalms]]. At least three of these readings and associated psalms must be read, which must include the account of the first [[Passover]] from the [[Book of Exodus]]. [[pastoral care|Pastoral]] conditions are taken into account when deciding on the number of readings.<ref name=\"Catholic culture\">[http://www.catholicculture.org/culture/liturgicalyear/activities/view.cfm?id=1043 Catholic Culture] accessed 12 August 2010</ref><ref name=USCCB>[http://www.nccbuscc.org/liturgy/eastervigil.shtml United States Conference of Catholic Bishops]. Accessed 12 August 2010</ref><ref name=\"CL Vigil\">[http://www.catholicliturgy.com/index.cfm/FuseAction/documentText/Index/2/SubIndex/38/ContentIndex/327/Start/319 Catholic Liturgy, Easter Sunday of the Lord's Resurrection, The Easter Vigil]. Accessed 12 August 2010</ref> These readings account salvation history, beginning with Creation. In Anglican worship, there are nine possible readings from the [[Old Testament]], and a minimum of two must be read, which must include the account of Israel's deliverance at the Red Sea.\n\nIn Catholic practice, during the [[Gloria in Excelsis Deo|Gloria]] at the Mass, the organ and church bells are used in the liturgy for the first time in two days.<ref>Catholic City  [http://www.catholicity.com/encyclopedia/h/holy_week.html Tenbrae] Retrieved on April 5, 2007</ref>  If the lights of the Church have been previously left off, they are turned on as the Gloria begins. The Paschal candle is used to bless the [[baptismal font]] to be used in the celebration of the sacrament.  The Great Alleluia is sung before the Gospel is read, [[Alleluia]] being used for the first time since before Lent. People receiving full initiation in the Church, who have completed their training, are given the Sacraments of [[Rite of Christian Initiation of Adults|Christian initiation]] ([[Baptism]], [[Confirmation (Christian sacrament)|confirmation]], and the [[Holy Eucharist]]). In Catholic and Anglican tradition, the Easter Vigil is an especially appropriate day for Holy Baptism.\n\nIn current practice, the use of lighting to signify the emergence from [[sin]] and the resurrection of Jesus varies, from the use of candles held by parishioners as well as [[candelabra]]s lit throughout the church.  If statues and images have been veiled during the last two weeks of Lent, they are unveiled, without ceremony, before the Easter Vigil service begins.<ref name=veiling/> (In the 1962 Catholic missal and earlier missals, they are unveiled during the \"Gloria in Excelsis\" of the Easter Vigil Mass.)\n\nColor of vestments and hangings: white, often together with gold, with yellow and white flowers often in use in many parishes.\n\nEaster Masses are held throughout the day and are similar in content to the Easter Vigil Mass. Jesus was a good man and so is Rozz\n\n{{Lent_calendar.svg}}\n\n==Easter time==\n{{Main|Eastertide}}\nThe date of Easter [[Easter#Date|varies from year to year]]. It occurs on the first Sunday after the first full moon on or after 21 March, a date taken, in accordance with an ancient ecclesiastical tradition, to be that of the spring equinox, but which does not always correspond to the astronomical equinox. The [[Julian Calendar]] is taken as the basis of the calculations by nearly all [[Oriental Orthodox]] and [[Eastern Orthodox Church]]es and is accepted even by [[Latin Church]] Catholics in countries such as [[Ethiopia]] and [[Greece]].   In the 20th and 21st centuries, the Julian Calendar's 21 March corresponds to 3 April in the [[Gregorian Calendar]], the calendar used for civil purposes in most countries. The earliest possible date for Easter is 22 March, and the latest 25 April. These dates in the Julian Calendar now correspond to the Gregorian Calendar's 4 April and 8 May.\n\nDuring the Easter [[Octave (liturgical)|octave]] (and also during Holy Week) no other feast is celebrated. If Easter is very early, the solemnity of the [[Annunciation]] (25 March) may fall within the octave or Holy Week and is then transferred to the Monday after the octave.<ref>Universal Norms on the Calendar, 60. This is an exception to the normal rule that impeded solemnities are transferred to the closest day not ranked as feast or higher.</ref>\n\nThe Sundays of Advent, Lent, and Easter have precedence over all feasts and solemnities, solemnities being then transferred to the following Monday, unless they occur on Palm Sunday or on Sunday of the Lord's Resurrection.<ref>Universal Norms on the Calendar, 5</ref> \"The Solemnity of Saint Joseph, where it is observed as a Holyday of Obligation, should it fall on Palm Sunday of the Lord's Passion, is anticipated on the preceding Saturday, 18 March. Where, on the other hand, it is not observed as a Holyday of Obligation, it may be transferred by the Conference of Bishops to another day outside Lent.\"<ref>Universal Norms on the Calendar, 56</ref>\n\nThe solemnity of the [[Ascension of Jesus Christ|Ascension]] is on the fortieth day of Easter, which is always a Thursday, although it may be observed on the following Sunday. [[Pentecost]] (or [[Whitsun]]) is the fiftieth day.\n\nThe Easter season extends from the Easter Vigil through Pentecost Sunday on the Roman Catholic, Anglo-Catholic and Protestant calendars. In the pre-1970 Roman Catholic calendar the octave of Pentecost is included in Eastertide, which thus ends at [[None (liturgy)|None]] of the following [[Ember Saturday]].\n\nDuring the 50-day Easter period, vestments are generally white or gold, but red when celebrating apostles and martyrs and on the solemnity of Pentecost. In the pre-1970 Roman Catholic calendar, with its 56-day Eastertide, red was used during the octave of Pentecost.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Holy Week]]\n*[[Holy Week procession]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.usccb.org/liturgy/triduumquestions.shtml Eighteen Questions on the Paschal Triduum]\n*[http://www.gbod.org/site/apps/nlnet/content3.aspx?c=nhLRJ2PMKsG&b=5560695&ct=7793155#notes The Three Days (The United Methodist Church GBOD)]\n\n{{Easter}}\n{{Liturgical year of the Catholic Church}}\n\n[[Category:Catholic liturgy]]\n[[Category:Catholic spirituality]]\n[[Category:Holy Week]]\n[[Category:Catholic devotions]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Meister des Hausbuches 003.jpg|thumb|''Christ Washing the Feet of the Apostles'' by Meister des Hausbuches, 1475 ([[Gem\u00e4ldegalerie]], [[Berlin]])]]\nThe '''Paschal Triduum''' ([[Latin]]: ''Triduum Paschale''),<ref>For the etymology of the term ''Paschal'' see ''[[Names of Easter#From Greek Pascha|Names of Easter]]''.</ref> '''Holy Triduum''' (Latin: ''Triduum Sacrum''), or '''Easter Triduum''', or the '''Three Days''',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elca.org/Growing-In-Faith/Worship/Planning/Three-Days.aspx|title=The Three Days: Maundy Thursday, Good Friday, and the Vigil of Easter|year=2012|publisher=[[Evangelical Lutheran Church in America]]|accessdate=1 April 2012}}</ref> is the period of three days that begins with the liturgy on the evening of [[Maundy Thursday]],<ref name=\"CL Thurs\">[http://www.catholicliturgy.com/index.cfm/FuseAction/documentText/Index/2/SubIndex/38/ContentIndex/324/Start/319 Catholic Liturgy, Holy Thursday Evening Mass of the Lord's Supper]</ref> reaches its high point in the [[Easter Vigil]], and closes with evening prayer on [[Easter Sunday]]. <ref name=General>[http://www.catholicliturgy.com/index.cfm/FuseAction/documentText/Index/2/SubIndex/38/ContentIndex/101/Start/97 General Norms for the Liturgical Year and the Calendar, 19]</ref> It recalls the [[Passion (Christianity)|Passion]], [[Crucifixion of Jesus|Crucifixion]], [[Crucifixion of Jesus|Death]], [[entombment of Christ|burial]], and [[Resurrection of Jesus]], as portrayed in the [[canonical Gospels]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bibleresources.americanbible.org/bible-resources/bible</ref>\n\nIn the [[Anglican]], [[Lutheran]], [[Methodist]], and [[Reformed]] traditions, the Paschal Triduum straddles the two liturgical seasons of [[Lent]] and [[Eastertide|Easter]] in the [[Church calendar]]; however, in the [[Roman Catholic]] tradition, since the [[Pope Pius XII#Liturgy reforms|1955 reform]] by [[Pope Pius XII]], the Easter Triduum has been more clearly distinguished as a separate liturgical period. Previously, all these celebrations were advanced by more than twelve hours. The [[Mass of the Lord's Supper]] and the [[Easter Vigil]] were celebrated in the morning of Thursday and Saturday respectively, and [[Holy Week]] and [[Lent]] were seen as ending only on the approach of Easter.\n\nAfter the [[Gloria in excelsis Deo]] at the Mass of the Lord's Supper, all church bells are silenced and the organ is not used. The period that lasted from Thursday morning to before Easter Sunday began was once, in Anglo-Saxon times, referred to as \"the still days\".<ref>{{CathEncy|wstitle=Holy Week}}</ref>\n\nIn the Catholic Church, [[wedding]]s, which were once prohibited throughout the entire season of Lent and during certain other periods as well,<ref>{{CathEncy|wstitle=Banns of Marriage}}</ref> are prohibited during the Triduum. Lutherans still discourage weddings during the entirety of Holy Week and the Easter Triduum.\n\n==Maundy Thursday (also called Holy Thursday)==\n[[File:Chancel of Houston Memorial UMC on Good Friday.jpg|thumb|350px|On Maundy Thursday, the [[Stripping of the Altar|altar of this Methodist church was stripped]] and the crucifix of this Methodist church was veiled in black for Good Friday (black is the liturgical colour for Good Friday in the United Methodist Church). A wooden cross sits in front of the bare chancel for the veneration of the cross ceremony, which occurs during the United Methodist Good Friday liturgy.]] \n{{Main|Maundy Thursday}}\n{{Liturgical year}}\nIn some Protestant denominations, the Triduum begins with an evening [[service of worship|worship service]] on [[Maundy Thursday]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liturgybytlw.com/Lent/MaunFW.html|title=The Triduum: Maundy Thursday with Footwashing|quote=The Maundy Thursday service is one of endings and beginnings. What was begun on Ash Wednesday is brought to a close here today. What begins today does not end until the resurrection of Easter. It is the ancient Triduum, \"The Three Sacred Days,\" which lead us to Easter: Maundy Thursday, Good Friday, and Holy Saturday.|publisher=[[Evangelical Lutheran Church in America]]|author=Rev. Thomas L. Weitzel|accessdate=1 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Catholic Church]] and in the [[Anglo-Catholic]] tradition of Anglicanism, in the [[Mass of the Lord's Supper]], during the [[Gloria in Excelsis Deo]], all church bells may be rung and the organ played; afterwards, bells and organ are silenced until the Gloria of the Easter Vigil.<ref name=\"CL Thurs\">[http://www.catholicliturgy.com/index.cfm/FuseAction/documentText/Index/2/SubIndex/38/ContentIndex/324/Start/319 Catholic Liturgy, Holy Thursday Evening Mass of the Lord's Supper]</ref> After the [[homily]] or [[sermon]] of the Mass, \"where a pastoral reason suggests it\", a ritual [[washing of the feet]] follows.<ref name=\"CL Thurs\" /><ref>''Roman Missal'', \"Thursday of the Lord's Supper\", 10</ref> The Mass concludes with a procession of the [[Blessed Sacrament]] to the [[altar of repose]].<ref name=\"CL Thurs\" /> In the [[Anglican]] tradition, this is usually followed by the stripping of the altars. [[Eucharistic adoration]] is encouraged after this, but if continued after midnight should be done without outward solemnity.<ref name=\"CL Thurs\" /> In the form of the [[Roman Rite]] in use before 1955, Mass was celebrated in the morning. Some faithful travelled to several churches to pray at each one's Altar of Repose, a practice called [[Seven Churches Visitation]], which now is associated rather with the morning of Good Friday. The Mass included no washing of the feet, which could instead be done in a separate ceremony later in the day. The Mass itself concluded with a ritual [[Stripping of the Altar|stripping]] of all altars except the altar of repose, leaving only the cross and candlesticks. In the present form as revised in 1955, the altar is stripped bare without ceremony at some time after the evening Mass.\n\nThe [[liturgical colour]] for the Mass vestments and other ornaments is white in the Catholic and Anglican Churches.<ref>[http://www.liturgyoffice.org.uk/Resources/GIRM/Documents/GIRM.pdf General Instruction of the Roman Missal, 346]</ref> In the Lutheran Church, the liturgical colour for Maundy Thursday is white.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elca.org/Growing-In-Faith/Worship/Learning-Center/FAQs/Liturgical-Colors.aspx|title=What is the meaning and use of liturgical colors?|publisher=[[Evangelical Lutheran Church in America]]|quote=Maundy Thursday: For this fourth day of Holy Week, celebrated as the institution of the Lord\u2019s Supper, scarlet or white is used.|accessdate=1 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404093828/http://www.elca.org/Growing-In-Faith/Worship/Learning-Center/FAQs/Liturgical-Colors.aspx|archivedate=4 April 2012}}</ref> In the [[Reformed]] tradition, white or gold may be used.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucc.org/worship/liturgies/liturgical-colors.html?print=t|title=Liturgical Colors and the seasons of the church year|publisher=[[United Church of Christ]]|quote=On Maundy Thursday, White or Gold symbolizes the church's rejoicing in the sacrament of the Lord's Supper. But at the end of the Maundy Thursday celebration, the mood changes abruptly: all decorations are removed and the Holy Table is stripped bare. The church becomes as empty as a tomb. On Good Friday, either Black or Red is customary\u2014although the use of no color at all is also appropriate.|accessdate=1 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427221700/http://www.ucc.org/worship/liturgies/liturgical-colors.html?print=t|archivedate=27 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Good Friday==\n[[File:Ecce homo by Antonio Ciseri (1).jpg|thumb|''[[Ecce Homo]]'' by [[Antonio Ciseri]] (19th century).]]\n{{Main|Good Friday}}\n\nOn Good Friday, Christians recall the [[Passion (Christianity)|passion]] and crucifixion of Jesus.\n\nIn the Roman Catholic, Lutheran, and Anglo-Catholic rites, a cross or crucifix (not necessarily the one that stands on or near the altar on other days of the year) is ceremonially unveiled.<ref>{{CathEncy|wstitle=Good Friday}}</ref> (In pre-1955 services, other crucifixes were to be unveiled, without ceremony, after the Good Friday service.)  In the Catholic ritual, [[clergy]] traditionally begin the service [[prostration|prostrate]] in front of the altar. Mass is not celebrated on Good Friday and the communion distributed at the Celebration of the Lord's Passion is consecrated on Holy Thursday, hence the pre-1955 name \"Mass of the Presanctified\". In Anglican churches, there is no prayer of consecration on Good Friday, and the Reserved Sacrament is distributed at services on that day.  Also in Catholicism, images of saints may, in accordance with local custom, be veiled throughout the last two weeks of Lent. Votive lights before these images are not lit. Crucifixes that are movable are hidden, while those that are not movable are veiled until after the Good Friday service.<ref name=veiling>[http://www.ewtn.com/library/liturgy/zlitur72.htm Covering of Crosses and Images in Lent]</ref> Catholic faithful typically venerate the crucifix by kissing the feet of the corpus. Veneration of a simple wooden cross is common in Anglican worship, with the faithful touching or kissing it.\n\nColors of vestments (and hangings, if kept) vary: no color, red, or black are used in different traditions. The Catholic Church uses red vestments, symbolic of the blood of Jesus Christ, but in the pre-1970 form of the [[Roman Missal]] the priest wears black, changing to violet for the communion part of the service. In Anglican services, [[black vestments]] are sometimes used. In [[The United Methodist Church]], black is the liturgical colour used on Good Friday.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=do7TAAAAMAAJ&q=liturgical+colors+Good+Friday+United+Methodist+Methodist&dq=liturgical+colors+Good+Friday+United+Methodist+Methodist&hl=en&sa=X&ei=agl6T-qZNcbc0QHTltmZDQ&ved=0CGQQ6AEwBg|title=Christian Advocate, Volume 5|publisher=[[The United Methodist Church]]|year=1961|quote=The liturgical color for the Lenten season is violet or purple, except for Good Friday when black is used.|accessdate=1 April 2012}}</ref>  In the [[Lutheran]] churches, there is no liturgical color on Good Friday.  Altars remain stripped and clergy wear no vestments on this day.\n\n==Holy Saturday==\n[[File:Resurrection.JPG|thumb|250px|''Jesus Resurrected'' by [[Piero della Francesca]] (15th century).]] \n\nAlso called Black Saturday, is a vigil service that is held after nightfall on Holy Saturday, or before dawn on Easter Sunday, in commemoration Jesus' death and [[harrowing of Hell]]. Many of the details that follow hold for Anglican and Evangelical Lutheran churches as well as Catholic worship.  The ceremony of darkness and light is held at the beginning of the [[Easter Vigil]] Mass. The [[paschal candle]], whose lighting symbolizes the resurrection of Christ from the dead,<ref>[http://www.elca.org/Growing-In-Faith/Worship/Learning-Center/FAQs/Paschal-Candle.aspx How do we use a paschal candle]</ref> is lit from the new Easter fire. The solemn procession to the altar with the Paschal candle is formed. Once everyone has processed in, the [[Exsultet]] is intoned.\n\nAfter the Exsultet, everyone is seated and listens to seven readings from the [[Old Testament]] and seven [[Psalms]]. At least three of these readings and associated psalms must be read, which must include the account of the first [[Passover]] from the [[Book of Exodus]]. [[pastoral care|Pastoral]] conditions are taken into account when deciding on the number of readings.<ref name=\"Catholic culture\">[http://www.catholicculture.org/culture/liturgicalyear/activities/view.cfm?id=1043 Catholic Culture] accessed 12 August 2010</ref><ref name=USCCB>[http://www.nccbuscc.org/liturgy/eastervigil.shtml United States Conference of Catholic Bishops]. Accessed 12 August 2010</ref><ref name=\"CL Vigil\">[http://www.catholicliturgy.com/index.cfm/FuseAction/documentText/Index/2/SubIndex/38/ContentIndex/327/Start/319 Catholic Liturgy, Easter Sunday of the Lord's Resurrection, The Easter Vigil]. Accessed 12 August 2010</ref> These readings account salvation history, beginning with Creation. In Anglican worship, there are nine possible readings from the [[Old Testament]], and a minimum of two must be read, which must include the account of Israel's deliverance at the Red Sea.\n\nIn Catholic practice, during the [[Gloria in Excelsis Deo|Gloria]] at the Mass, the organ and church bells are used in the liturgy for the first time in two days.<ref>Catholic City  [http://www.catholicity.com/encyclopedia/h/holy_week.html Tenbrae] Retrieved on April 5, 2007</ref>  If the lights of the Church have been previously left off, they are turned on as the Gloria begins. The Paschal candle is used to bless the [[baptismal font]] to be used in the celebration of the sacrament.  The Great Alleluia is sung before the Gospel is read, [[Alleluia]] being used for the first time since before Lent. People receiving full initiation in the Church, who have completed their training, are given the Sacraments of [[Rite of Christian Initiation of Adults|Christian initiation]] ([[Baptism]], [[Confirmation (Christian sacrament)|confirmation]], and the [[Holy Eucharist]]). In Catholic and Anglican tradition, the Easter Vigil is an especially appropriate day for Holy Baptism.\n\nIn current practice, the use of lighting to signify the emergence from [[sin]] and the resurrection of Jesus varies, from the use of candles held by parishioners as well as [[candelabra]]s lit throughout the church.  If statues and images have been veiled during the last two weeks of Lent, they are unveiled, without ceremony, before the Easter Vigil service begins.<ref name=veiling/> (In the 1962 Catholic missal and earlier missals, they are unveiled during the \"Gloria in Excelsis\" of the Easter Vigil Mass.)\n\nColor of vestments and hangings: white, often together with gold, with yellow and white flowers often in use in many parishes.\n\nEaster Masses are held throughout the day and are similar in content to the Easter Vigil Mass.\n\n{{Lent_calendar.svg}}\n\n==Easter time==\n{{Main|Eastertide}}\nThe date of Easter [[Easter#Date|varies from year to year]]. It occurs on the first Sunday after the first full moon on or after 21 March, a date taken, in accordance with an ancient ecclesiastical tradition, to be that of the spring equinox, but which does not always correspond to the astronomical equinox. The [[Julian Calendar]] is taken as the basis of the calculations by nearly all [[Oriental Orthodox]] and [[Eastern Orthodox Church]]es and is accepted even by [[Latin Church]] Catholics in countries such as [[Ethiopia]] and [[Greece]].   In the 20th and 21st centuries, the Julian Calendar's 21 March corresponds to 3 April in the [[Gregorian Calendar]], the calendar used for civil purposes in most countries. The earliest possible date for Easter is 22 March, and the latest 25 April. These dates in the Julian Calendar now correspond to the Gregorian Calendar's 4 April and 8 May.\n\nDuring the Easter [[Octave (liturgical)|octave]] (and also during Holy Week) no other feast is celebrated. If Easter is very early, the solemnity of the [[Annunciation]] (25 March) may fall within the octave or Holy Week and is then transferred to the Monday after the octave.<ref>Universal Norms on the Calendar, 60. This is an exception to the normal rule that impeded solemnities are transferred to the closest day not ranked as feast or higher.</ref>\n\nThe Sundays of Advent, Lent, and Easter have precedence over all feasts and solemnities, solemnities being then transferred to the following Monday, unless they occur on Palm Sunday or on Sunday of the Lord's Resurrection.<ref>Universal Norms on the Calendar, 5</ref> \"The Solemnity of Saint Joseph, where it is observed as a Holyday of Obligation, should it fall on Palm Sunday of the Lord's Passion, is anticipated on the preceding Saturday, 18 March. Where, on the other hand, it is not observed as a Holyday of Obligation, it may be transferred by the Conference of Bishops to another day outside Lent.\"<ref>Universal Norms on the Calendar, 56</ref>\n\nThe solemnity of the [[Ascension of Jesus Christ|Ascension]] is on the fortieth day of Easter, which is always a Thursday, although it may be observed on the following Sunday. [[Pentecost]] (or [[Whitsun]]) is the fiftieth day.\n\nThe Easter season extends from the Easter Vigil through Pentecost Sunday on the Roman Catholic, Anglo-Catholic and Protestant calendars. In the pre-1970 Roman Catholic calendar the octave of Pentecost is included in Eastertide, which thus ends at [[None (liturgy)|None]] of the following [[Ember Saturday]].\n\nDuring the 50-day Easter period, vestments are generally white or gold, but red when celebrating apostles and martyrs and on the solemnity of Pentecost. In the pre-1970 Roman Catholic calendar, with its 56-day Eastertide, red was used during the octave of Pentecost.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Holy Week]]\n*[[Holy Week procession]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.usccb.org/liturgy/triduumquestions.shtml Eighteen Questions on the Paschal Triduum]\n*[http://www.gbod.org/site/apps/nlnet/content3.aspx?c=nhLRJ2PMKsG&b=5560695&ct=7793155#notes The Three Days (The United Methodist Church GBOD)]\n\n{{Easter}}\n{{Liturgical year of the Catholic Church}}\n\n[[Category:Catholic liturgy]]\n[[Category:Catholic spirituality]]\n[[Category:Holy Week]]\n[[Category:Catholic devotions]]\n", "name_user": "72.234.59.60", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHoly Saturday)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paschal_Triduum"}
