r/en/middle-east/syrian-tribes-vow-popular-resistance-against-pkk-pyd/828919|title=Syrian tribes vow \u2018popular resistance\u2019 against PKK/PYD|website=Aa.com.tr}}</ref>\n{{Flagicon image|Flag of the Al-Nusra Front.svg}} [[al-Nusra Front]] remnants {{small|(allegedly)}}<br>'''Supported by:'''<br>{{flag|Turkey}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ypgrojava.org/Turkish-backed-sleeper-cells-captured-by-our-forces|title=Turkish-backed sleeper cells captured by our forces &#124; English|website=www.ypgrojava.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://anfenglish.com/features/orders-from-the-mIt-murders-from-the-kiyam-movement-26047|title=Orders from the M\u0130T, murders from the Kiyam Movement|website=ANF News}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://iswresearch.blogspot.com/2017/11/post-isis-insurgency-looms-in-northern.html|title=ISW Blog: Post-ISIS Insurgency Looms in Northern Syria|first=Institute For The Study Of|last=War|date=November 7, 2017}}</ref>\n| combatant2  = {{flagdeco|Democratic Federation of Northern Syria}} [[Rojava]]{{efn|Known as \"Democratic Federation of Northern Syria\" until September 2018, and as \"Autonomous Administration of North and East Syria\" afterwards. }}\n*{{flagicon image|Flag of Syrian Democratic Forces.svg}} [[Syrian Democratic Forces]]\n*{{flagicon image|Infobox HXP.svg|border=no}} [[Self-Defense Forces (DFNS regions)|Self-Defence Forces]] (HXP)\n*{{flagicon image|Asayish infobox flag.png}} [[Asayish (NES regions)|Internal Security Forces]] (Asayish)\n[[File:Seal of Combined Joint Task Force \u2013 Operation Inherent Resolve.svg|23px]] [[CJTF\u2013OIR]]\n*{{flag|United States}}\n'''Supported by:'''<br>{{flagicon image|Flag_of_Kurdistan_Workers_Party_(PKK).svg}} [[Kurdistan Workers' Party]] ({{small|PKK, claimed by Turkey, ISIL and the Popular Resistance}})\n| commander1  = {{flagdeco|ISIL}} Thabit Sobhi Fahd Al-Ahmad{{KIA}}<ref name=\"oil minister\"/><br/>{{small|(ISIL oil minister)}}<br/>{{flagdeco|ISIL}} Mohammed Remedan Eyd al-Talah{{POW}}<ref name=\"financial officer\"/><br/>{{small|(ISIL chief financial officer)}}\n| commander2  = {{flagicon image|Flag of Syrian Democratic Forces.svg}} [[Mazlum Kobane]]<br/>{{small|(SDF commander-in-chief)}}<br/>{{flagdeco|United States}} Eric T. Hill<ref name=\"financial officer\"/><br/>{{small|(SOJTF commander)}}\n| units1      = {{flagdeco|ISIL}} [[Military of ISIL]]\n*Insurgent forces\n**Army of the Security Forces<ref>{{cite web|author=Assad Al Mohammad|url=https://extremism.gwu.edu/sites/g/files/zaxdzs2191/f/The%20Islamic%20State%27s%20Effort%20to%20Co-Opt%20Tanzim%20Hurras%20Ad-Din.pdf|title=The Islamic State's effort to co-opt Tanzim Hurras ad-Din|website=Program on Extremism: The George Washington University|date=November 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Clandestine cell system|Sleeper cells]]<ref name=\"financial officer\"/>\n|units2      = {{flagicon image|Flag of Syrian Democratic Forces.svg}} Syrian Democratic Forces\n*[[People's Protection Units|YPG]]\n*[[Women's Protection Units|YPJ]]\n*[[Anti-Terror Units]]<ref name=\"financial officer\"/>\n[[File:Seal of Combined Joint Task Force \u2013 Operation Inherent Resolve.svg|23px]] CJTF\u2013OIR\n*Special Operations Joint Task Force (SOJTF)<ref name=\"financial officer\"/>\n| strength1   = {{flagdeco|ISIL}} Unknown, probably thousands<ref name=\"desert-based\"/>\n| strength2   = {{flagicon image|Flag of Syrian Democratic Forces.svg}} 60,000\u201375,000 <small>(2017 estimate)</small><ref name=\"military and security structures\">{{cite book|last=Rashid|first=Bedir Mulla|translator=Obaida Hitto|title= Military and Security Structures of the Autonomous Administration in Syria|url=http://omranstudies.org/publications/reports/download/68_d403f01ed28320cb2e67b13cffb381c7.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180701140230/http://omranstudies.org/publications/reports/download/68_d403f01ed28320cb2e67b13cffb381c7.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2018-07-01|orig-year=1st pub. 2017|date= 2018|publisher= Omran for Strategic Studies|location= [[Istanbul]]|ref=harv}}</ref><br/>{{flagicon|United States}} {{circa}} 2,000 <small>(2018 estimate)</small><ref name=\"sights\" />\n| casualties1 = '''ISIL''': 204 killed, 107 captured, 161 wounded <small>(2018)</small><ref name=2018balance>[https://www.ypgrojava.org/Results-of-battles-and-resistance-of-YPG-throughout-2018 Results of battles and resistance of YPG throughout 2018]<br>[https://anfenglishmobile.com/rojava-northern-syria/ypg-2422-turkish-soldiers-and-mercenaries-killed-in-2018-31870 YPG: 2422 Turkish soldiers and mercenaries killed in 2018]</ref><br>42 captured <small>(2019)</small><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://southfront.org/sdf-announces-results-of-its-recent-security-operation-in-southern-deir-ezzor-photos/|title=SDF Announces Results Of Its Recent Security Operation In Southeastern Deir Ezzor (Photos)|date=May 17, 2019}}</ref>\n| casualties2 = '''SDF''': 309 killed <small>(vs IS; Aug. 2018-March 2020)</small><ref name=syriahr>{{Cite web|url=http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=157841|title=ISIS resurgence: SDF fighter stabbed to death east of Deir Ezzor \u2022 The Syrian Observatory For Human Rights|date=March 22, 2020}}</ref><br>5 killed <small>(vs TAF; 2018)</small><ref name=2018balance/><br>'''Coalition:''' 6 killed<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/us-military-syria-coalition-service-members-killed-manbij-explosion-2018-3-30/|title=American service member, British armed forces member killed in Syria|website=www.cbsnews.com}}</ref></small><ref name=syriahr/>\n| casualties3 = 151 civilians killed <small>(Aug. 2018-February 2020)</small><ref name=syriahr/>\n| notes       = \n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Syrian Civil War}}\n{{Campaignbox Rojava Revolution}}\n}}\nThe '''Eastern Syria insurgency''' is an armed [[insurgency]] being waged by remnants of the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) and both pro and anti-[[Syrian government]] [[Arab nationalism|Arab nationalist]] insurgents, against the [[Rojava|Autonomous Administration of North and East Syria]], its military (the [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] (SDF)), and their allies in the US-led [[Combined Joint Task Force \u2013 Operation Inherent Resolve]] (CJTF\u2013OIR) coalition.\n\n==Background==\n{{Further|Rojava\u2013Islamist conflict (2013\u2013present)}}\nThe insurgency began after a series of campaigns in 2016 and 2017 which took territory from the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]], led by the [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] and the [[CJTF-OIR]]. This eventually resulted in the taking of the Islamic State capital of [[Raqqa]], and other areas in the [[Aleppo Governorate|Aleppo]], [[Raqqa Governorate|Raqqa]] and [[Deir ez-Zor Governorate]]s. These are Arab-majority areas, often with large [[Syrian Turkmen|Turkmen]] minorities, some of whom resented the [[Kurd]]ish influence in the SDF.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://iswresearch.blogspot.com/2017/11/post-isis-insurgency-looms-in-northern.html|title=ISW Blog: Post-ISIS Insurgency Looms in Northern Syria|date=7 November 2017|website=Iswresearch.blogspot.com}}</ref>\n\nMultiple factions, made up mostly of Arabs, have formed armed groups in support of either the [[Syrian opposition]] or Syrian government, with additional Islamic State remnants operating as [[clandestine cell system|clandestine cells]] who have emerged in areas captured by the SDF and the coalition during the 2016-2017 campaigns. These groups have also utilized [[guerilla tactics]] to target the SDF and Coalition forces, including assassinations, [[Hit-and-run tactics|hit and run attacks]], rocket attacks and use of [[improvised explosive devices]] (IEDs). Attacks have occurred in cities across Rojava, including [[Manbij]], Raqqa and [[Hasakah]].\n\n==Insurgent factions==\n*'''Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant:''' Following the loss of most of its territory, the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant has launched a desert-based insurgency, while simultaneously attempting to rally elements of the civilian population to its cause. By attacking SDF-backed civil authorities, it undermines the latter's reputation and worsens existing grievances, resulting in a deteriorating security situation. It is unclear how many active ISIL fighters still operate in Syria, but they probably number several thousands.<ref name=\"desert-based\">{{cite web| url = https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2019/08/islamic-state-wages-desert-based-insurgency-in-iraq-and-syria.php| title = Islamic State wages desert-based insurgency in Iraq and Syria|author=Thomas Joscelyn | work = Long War Journal| date = 7 August 2018 | access-date = 8 August 2019}}</ref>\n*'''Government loyalists:''' Various pro-government groups operate in eastern Syria, including the \"[[Popular Resistance of the Eastern Region]]\" (founded in February 2018 in Raqqa), the \"Popular Resistance in Hasakah\" (founded in April 2018),<ref name=memri>{{cite web| url = https://www.memri.org/reports/syrian-threats-against-us-presence-syria-continue-us-troops-bases-are-our-sights-and-will| title = Syrian Threats Against The U.S. Presence In Syria Continue: U.S. Troops, Bases Are In Our Sights And Will Pay A Heavy Price | date = 2 May 2018| work = MEMRI| access-date = 2 August 2019}}</ref> and the \"Popular Resistance in Manbij\" (founded in June 2018).<ref name=southfront>{{cite web| url = https://southfront.org/popular-resistance-in-manbij-announces-uprising-against-foreign-occupiers/| title = \"Popular Resistance in Manbij\" Announces Uprising Against Foreign Occupiers | date = 25 June 2018| work = SouthFront| access-date = 2 August 2019}}</ref> These groups are reportedly supported by [[Iran]],<ref name=\"outpacing\"/> and elements of the [[Syrian Armed Forces]] such as the [[Baqir Brigade]].<ref name=memri/> The loyalist militants are not very active, however, and have carried out relatively few attacks.<ref name=southfront/>\n\n==Timeline==\n===2017===\n*'''November -''' [[Harakat al-Qiyam]] attempted to assassinate SDF commander Muhammad Abu Adel with an IED in [[Manbij]], leaving him injured.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://syria.liveuamap.com/en/2017/5-november-fsa-qiyam-movement-claims-the-responsibility-of|title=FSA Qiyam Movement claims the responsibility of them targeting \"Abu Adel\" the newly appointed leader of MMC in Manbij by an IED|website=Syria.liveuamap.com}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\n*'''5 April -''' The Popular Resistance claimed to have carried out a mortar or rocket attack on a U.S. base at [[Ayn Issa]].<ref name=\"sights\">{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/04/16/iranian-backed-militias-set-sights-on-u-s-forces/ |title=Iranian-Backed Militias Set Sights on U.S. Forces |author=Borzou Daragahi |work=Foreign Policy |date=16 April 2018 |accessdate=25 April 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"outpacing\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtoninstitute.org/policy-analysis/view/iran-is-outpacing-assad-for-control-of-syrias-shia-militias |title= Iran Is Outpacing Assad for Control of Syria's Shia Militias |author=Phillip Smyth |work=Washington Institute |date=12 April 2018 |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n*'''6 April -''' The [[Baqir Brigade]] vowed to aid the pro-government insurgency in territories held by U.S.-allied forces.<ref name=\"sights\"/><ref name=\"outpacing\"/>\n*'''2 September -'''  5 SDF militiamen were killed and wounded by an IED planted in [[Raqqa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.zamanalwsl.net/news/article/37194/|title=Raqqa: five SDF fighters killed and wounded in IED|website=En.zamanalwsl.net}}</ref>\n*'''31 October -''' The Turkish military and SDF began [[2018 northern Syria border clashes|clashes]] with stated future goals of a Turkish-led operation in Manbij. The fighting lasted one week, with the United States responding by establishing observation posts in Manbij to prevent further violence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/211120182|title=US to establish observation posts on Syria-Turkey border: Mattis|website=Rudaw.net}}</ref>\n*'''2 November -''' ISIL gunmen assassinated the prominent tribal leader Sheikh Basheer Faisal al-Huwaidi in broad daylight in the city of Raqqa.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/ac9d25db-9bab-44ee-9922-e6b0fa71509a|title=Prominent Raqqa tribal leader assassinated in attack claimed by IS|website=Kurdistan24.net|accessdate=2018-11-02}}</ref>\n*'''4 November -''' A [[car bomb]] exploded in the city of Raqqa, killing at least one person and injuring ten more people, which included members of the SDF. ISIL claimed responsibility for the attack through its [[Amaq News Agency]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.euronews.com/2018/11/04/islamic-state-says-hits-syrias-raqqa-with-car-bomb|title=Islamic State says hits Syria's Raqqa with car bomb|website=Euronews.com|accessdate=2018-11-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ammonnews.net/article/410475|title=\u0633\u0648\u0631\u064a\u0627: \u0627\u0646\u0641\u062c\u0627\u0631 \u064a\u0647\u0632 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0642\u0629 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0634\u0627\u0626\u0631 \u062a\u062f\u0639\u0648 \u0625\u0644\u0649 \u0645\u0638\u0627\u0647\u0631\u0629 \u063a\u062f\u0627\u064b|website=Ammonnews.net|date=2018-11-04|access-date=2018-11-04|language=ar-AR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dostor.org/2384188|title=\u0645\u0642\u062a\u0644 \u0634\u062e\u0635 \u0648\u0625\u0635\u0627\u0628\u0629 10 \u0641\u064a \u0647\u062c\u0648\u0645 \u0628\u0633\u064a\u0627\u0631\u0629 \u0645\u0641\u062e\u062e\u0629 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0631\u0642\u0629|website=Dostor.org|date=2018-11-04|access-date=2018-11-04|language=ar-AR}}</ref>\n*'''4 December -''' YPG claimed to have arrested four members of Harakat al-Qiyam, allegedly collaborating with [[Turkish intelligence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ypgrojava.org/Turkish-backed-sleeper-cells-captured-by-our-forces|title=Turkish-backed sleeper cells captured by our forces - English|website=Ypgrojava.org}}</ref>\n\n[[File:US M-ATVs.jpg|thumb|right|U.S. [[Oshkosh M-ATV|M-ATV]]s patrolling the [[Manbij]] countryside, 14 July 2018]]\n\n===2019===\n*'''January 2019 -''' The founder of the [[Arab Ahwaz Brigade]], an Arab [[Free Syrian Army]] group from Deir ez-Zor, was killed by an IED planted by ISIL in Deir ez-Zor, he reportedly joined the [[Syrian Democratic Forces]] and became involved with its [[Syrian Democratic Forces military councils#Deir ez-Zor|Deir ez-Zor Military Council]] serving as a leader in the council.<ref>https://en.deirezzor24.net/one-of-the-most-prominent-military-leaders-in-deir-ezzor-and-one-of-the-first-defectors-from-assads-forces-abu-isaac-al-ahwazy-is-killed/</ref>\n\n*'''9 January 2019 -''' \"The Gathering of the Eastern Martyrs,\" a sub-unit of [[Ahrar al-Sharqiya]], claimed responsibility for bombing an SDF [[humvee]] with an IED.<ref>https://pbs.twimg.com/media/DwfwBQZWoAABH7e.jpg</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2019}}\n\n*'''16 January 2019 -''' [[Manbij bombing|An explosion went off in the city of Manbij]], killing 4 US soldiers as well as fighters from the Manbij Military Council. In total, at least 19 people lost their lives. ISIL claimed the attack through its news agency Amaq.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/16/politics/syria-attack-us-patrolled-city/index.html|title=4 Americans killed in Syria attack. ISIS claims responsibility|author=Zachary Cohen, Veronica Stracqualursi and Kevin Liptak|website=Cnn.com|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mideast-crisis-syria-blast-idUSKCN1PA1GQ|title=Blast claimed by Islamic State kills U.S. troops in Syria|date=16 January 2019|accessdate=3 February 2019|website=Reuters.com}}</ref>\n\n*'''21 January 2019 -''' An ISIL suicide [[car bomb|SVBIED]] targeted a US convoy accompanied by SDF troops on the [[Al-Shaddadah|Shadadi]]-Al-Hasakah road in [[Al-Hasakah Governorate|Al-Hasakah province]], killing 5 SDF personnel. Witnesses say the SVBIED rammed into an SDF vehicle by a checkpoint held by Kurdish forces a dozen kilometers outside Shadadi as the US convoy drove past. No Americans were harmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1439236/middle-east|title=Suicide attack on Kurdish-US convoy in Syria kills 5: monitor|date=21 January 2019|website=Arab News|accessdate=3 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n*'''7 February 2019 -''' The SDF media center announced the capture of 63 ISIL operatives in [[Raqqa]]. According to the Kurds, the operatives were a part of a [[sleeper cell]] and were all arrested within 24 hours, ending the day-long curfew that was imposed on the city the day before.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/over-60-isis-operatives-captured-in-raqqa-city/|title=Over 60 ISIS operatives captured in Raqqa city|first=News|last=Desk|date=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n*'''9 February 2019 -''' ISIL militants attacked SDF fighters near the al-Omar oilfield, triggering airstrikes by the U.S.-led Coalition. [[SOHR]] said 12 Islamic State fighters attacked SDF and clashed with them for several hours until most of the attackers were killed. Ten attackers were reportedly killed, while two managed to flee. Other activist collectives, including the Step news agency, reported the attack, saying some of the attackers used motorcycles rigged with explosives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/middle-east/us-backed-fighters-launch-final-push-defeat-syria|title=US-backed Fighters Launch Final Push to Defeat IS in Syria|website=Voice of America}}</ref>\n\n*'''21 February 2019 -''' 2 successive SVBIEDs detonated in the market area of Shahil, Syria - 10 kilometers from the SDF's al-Omar oilfield HQ - killing 14 people. SOHR reported a car bomb that was detonated remotely as a convoy of workers and technicians that worked at the oilfield was passing by. SOHR said 20 were killed and others wounded.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Two-car-bombings-in-Syria-kill-at-least-six-581401|title=Two car bombings in Syria kill at least six - Breaking News - Jerusalem Post|website=www.jpost.com|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.garda.com/crisis24/news-alerts/206771/syria-vbieds-kill-six-people-in-aleppo-province-february-21|title=Syria: VBIEDs kill six people in Aleppo province February 21|website=GardaWorld|language=en|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=Fox News|url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/the-latest-back-to-back-suicide-car-bombs-kill-14-in-syria|date=21 February 2019|title=The Latest: Back-to-back suicide car bombs kill 14 in Syria}}</ref> Other reports of this attack provided alternate locations of the VBIED explosions, the Northwestern city of Afrin and the village of Ghandura near Jarablus.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n*'''9 March 2019 -''' 8 people were wounded when a suicide bomber blew up a car in Manbij, near a market. The Islamic State claimed responsibility for the attack.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/5c652373-14ff-4c93-919f-674d949c1284|title=ISIS claims bombing in Syria\u2019s Manbij which left at least eight casualties|publisher=Kurdistan24|accessdate=2019-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rudaw.net/english/middleeast/syria/090320191|title=Suicide bomber strikes Syria's Manbij, injures 8: MMC|publisher=Rudaw|accessdate=2019-03-09}}</ref>\n\n*'''14 March 2019 -''' The pro-Syrian government Popular Resistance detonated an IED in Raqqa, targeting a military convoy. The group claimed that they had killed SDF fighters and injured U.S. soldiers, but these claims could not be independently verified.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/mysterious-pro-govt-group-allegedly-attacks-us-military-convoy-in-raqqa-video/|title=Mysterious pro-gov\u2019t group allegedly attacks US military convoy in Raqqa (video)|work=[[Al-Masdar News]]|accessdate=2019-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/sdf-troops-suffer-heavy-casualties-after-convoy-comes-under-attack-in-raqqa/ |title=SDF troops suffer heavy casualties after convoy comes under attack in Raqqa |work=[[al-Masdar News]] |date=3 April 2018| access-date = 12 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n*'''26 March 2019 -''' ISIL gunmen opened fire on a checkpoint in [[Manbij]], killing 7 [[Manbij Military Council]] fighters.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1472736/middle-east|title=Daesh militants kill 7 US-backed fighters in Syria: commanders|date=26 March 2019}}</ref> On the same day, ISIL claimed responsibility for three separate attacks in Deir ez-Zor.<ref>https://pbs.twimg.com/media/D2nNgycWwAI99NW.jpg</ref><ref>https://pbs.twimg.com/media/D2nNgybX4AQYXb4.jpg</ref><ref>https://pbs.twimg.com/media/D2nNgyjXQAEBWyw.jpg</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2019}}\n\n*'''3 April 2019 -''' An ISIL cell clashed with the SDF and the Asayish in Raqqa, with 4 ISIL fighters blowing themselves with explosive belts, according to SOHR.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=123155|title=(Pictures) Suicide bombings shake al-Raqqah city as part of the renew of ISIS sleeper cells activity as the security operation of SDF, their intelligence, and Asayish continues \u2022 The Syrian Observatory For Human Rights|date=April 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n*'''5 April 2019 -''' About 200 ISIL detainees [[D\u00earik prison escape attempt|revolted and attempted to escape from D\u00earik prison]] in [[al-Malikiyah]]. The breakout was foiled, and some of the prisoners were subsequently distributed to other detention centers.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.lci.fr/terrorisme/info-tf1-lci-syrie-des-cadres-djihadistes-francais-de-daech-impliques-dans-une-mutinerie-a-la-prison-kurde-de-derik-2118134.html |title=INFO TF1/LCI - Syrie : des cadres fran\u00e7ais de Daech impliqu\u00e9s dans une mutinerie |author=Georges Brenier |work=LCI |date=11 April 2019 |accessdate=12 April 2019 }}</ref>\n\n*'''10 April 2019 -''' ISIL cells attacked SDF fighters at a checkpoint in rural Deir Ez Zor on the outskirts of the town of al-Shuhayl, the cell reportedly used machine guns and [[RPG-7|RPGs]] during the attack, as part of a global campaign launched by ISIL, which the group has called \"The campaign in revenge for the blessed Province of the Levant\" after losing territorial control in Syria after the [[Battle of Baghuz Fawqani]], which has prompted the group to carry out a series of attacks around the world where the group has a presence, as well as encouraging supporters to carry out [[Lone wolf (terrorism)|lone wolf]] attacks in their countries, other attacks related to the group's call for vengeance have occurred in [[Libya]] and [[Iraq]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=123969|title=Within the \"revenge war for al-Sham State,\" ISIS cells carry out new attacks on sites and checkpoints of SDF east of Euphrates \u2022 The Syrian Observatory For Human Rights|date=April 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ent.siteintelgroup.com/Chatter/is-aligned-media-groups-incite-lone-wolf-attacks-globally-in-revenge-for-territorial-losses.html|title=IS-Aligned Media Groups Incite Lone-Wolf Attacks Globally in Revenge for Territorial Losses &#124; Chatter &#124; Jihadist News &#124; Articles|website=ent.siteintelgroup.com}}</ref><ref>https://pbs.twimg.com/media/D35XQikXsAAgUcx.jpg</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/isis-launches-operation-vengeance-for-sham-in-several-countries/|title=ISIS launches 'Operation Vengeance for Sham' in several countries|first=News|last=Desk|date=April 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n*'''12 April 2019 -''' ISIL claimed responsibility for an attack in Manbij against members of the SDF.<ref>https://pbs.twimg.com/media/D35tQ0MWsAgvRQs.jpg</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=April 2019}}\n\n*'''23 April 2019 -''' Major protests began in the cities of [[Al-Busayrah]] and Shuhail in the eastern part of the [[Deir ez-Zor Governorate]] in opposition to SDF and Kurdish rule.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-kurds-protests-idUSKCN1S40RD|title=Arabs in Syria's Deir al-Zor protest against ruling Kurdish...|date=28 April 2019|publisher=|access-date=16 May 2019|via=www.Reuters.com}}</ref>\n\n*'''7 May 2019 -''' A senior commander in the SDFs' Deir ez-Zor military council claimed that Iran, Turkey, and the Syrian government are collaborating to destabilize SDF controlled areas with fighters from [[Operation Euphrates Shield]] and [[al-Nusra]] remnant cells in eastern Syria. The commander also claimed there is ideological support for ISIL and al-Nusra among the local populations, particularly in the towns of Jadidat Agidat, Shehail, and Basira, which is a hub for Deir ez-Zor's tribes and has also been the site for recent protests against SDF administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://syrianobserver.com/EN/news/50029/three-civilians-killed-by-qasad-militia-at-a-protest.html|title=Three Civilians Killed by Qasad Militia at a Protest|date=April 26, 2019}}</ref> The commander also claimed that the SDF had foiled 180 attempted attacks against SDF, and claimed that Turkey and the Syrian Government provide support for these attacks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hawarnews.com/en/haber/sdf-commander-daesh-launched-nearly-180-attacks-over-a-month-all-were-failure-h8828.html|title=SDF commander: Daesh launched nearly 180 attacks over a month, all were failure - ANHA &#124; HAWARNEWS &#124; English|website=hawarnews.com}}</ref>\n\n*'''11 May 2019 -''' Unidentified gunmen attacked a YPG headquarters in the western part of the town of Shuhail, where ongoing protests against the SDF were occurring.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nedaa-sy.com/en/news/13475|title=Unknown gunmen target the headquarters of YPG militia in Deir Al-Zour|date=May 10, 2019|website=Call Syria}}</ref>\n\n*'''14 July 2019 -''' The SDF and U.S. special forces killed ISIL's oil minister Thabit Sobhi Fahd Al-Ahmad during a raid somewhere in Deir ez-Zor Governorate.<ref name=\"oil minister\">{{cite web| url = https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/isis-oil-minister-killed-in-eastern-syria/ | title = ISIS oil minister killed in eastern Syria |author= | work = [[al-Masdar News]] | date = 14 July 2019 | access-date = 22 July 2019 }}</ref>\n\n*'''1 September 2019 -''' The SDF's [[Anti-Terror Units]] captured Mohammed Remedan Eyd al-Talah, ISIL's chief financial officer, during a raid in ash-Shahil, Deir ez-Zor Governorate.<ref name=\"financial officer\">{{cite web| url = https://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/25437728-90de-473e-ba71-1623479a5775 | title = US-backed forces in Syria capture top ISIS financial officer |author= Wladimir van Wilgenburg | work = Kurdistan24 | date = 2 September 2019 | access-date = 3 September 2019 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bradley Convoy in Syria.jpg|thumb|A U.S. patrol accompanied by [[M2 Bradley#M2A2|M2A2 Bradley]] vehicles in eastern Syria, 10 November 2019]]\n*'''October 2019 -''' The U.S. withdrew from many of its bases in northern Syria in early October, substantially reducing its presence there and disrupting anti-ISIL operations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-49956698|title=Trump makes way for Turkey operation against Kurds in Syria|date=7 October 2019|work=BBC}}</ref> Nevertheless, the U.S., with Kurdish, Turkish and Iraqi assistance, conducted  a successful high-stakes [[Barisha raid|special operations raid]] in [[Barisha, Harem District|Barisha]], [[Idlib Governorate|Idlib]] targeting ISIL leader [[Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi]]; the raid resulted in Baghdadi's death and ISIL selecting a new leader, [[Abu Ibrahim al-Hashimi al-Qurashi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2019/11/islamic-state-confirms-baghdadis-death-names-new-emir-of-the-faithful.php|title=Islamic State confirms Baghdadi's death, names new 'Emir of the Faithful' {{!}} FDD's Long War Journal|date=2019-11-01|website=longwarjournal.org|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191101130040/https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2019/11/islamic-state-confirms-baghdadis-death-names-new-emir-of-the-faithful.php|archive-date=2019-11-01|url-status=live}}</ref> [[American-led intervention in the Syrian Civil War#October 2019: U.S. withdrawal from north Syria, return, & al-Baghdadi death|By the end of October]], the U.S. had adopted a subordinate mission to protect SDF-controlled oil and gas infrastructure, including oil fields, from the ISIL insurgency as the terror group had previously [[Oil production and smuggling in ISIL|used profits from oil smuggling]] to fund its activities. The U.S. deployed [[mechanized infantry]] units for the first time in its intervention to \"reinforce\" its presence in eastern Syria and to assist its continuing anti-ISIL insurgency mission.<ref>{{cite news|work=Associated Press|url=https://www.apnews.com/bb981d67e28c4f1599be8a94fabf5cbc|title=Not over yet: New US Syria mission after al-Baghdadi death}}</ref>\n\n*'''22 November 2019 -''' Coalition forces accompanied by allies attacked ISIL enclaves near the Iraqi border, which reportedly resulted in multiple ISIL fighters being killed and wounded.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inherentresolve.mil/Releases/News-Releases/Article/2025134/coalition-continues-operations-to-defeat-daesh-in-syria/|title=Coalition continues operations to defeat Daesh in Syria|website=inherentresolve.mil|date=23 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/25/us/politics/us-syria-isis.html|title=U.S. Resumes Large-Scale Operations Against ISIS in Northern Syria|website=The New York Times|date=25 November 2019}}</ref> While up to 600 ISIL fighters are thought to be defending a small pocket stronghold in Syria's eastern province of Deir ez-Zor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://stockdailydish.com/fighting-slows-final-push-against-is-in-eastern-syria/|title=Fighting slows \u2018final push\u2018 against IS in eastern Syria|website=Stock Daily Dish|date=25 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n*'''26 November 2019 -''' a car bomb went off in an area under the control of Turkish and allied rebel forces west of [[Ras al-Ayn]], killing at least 17 people and injuring 20 others. The attack happened at a local village market. The Turkish government blamed YPG and PKK for the attack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/d8a236f2c5634c95a5e79872088c8ff4|title=Turkish Defense Ministry says 17 killed in car bomb explosion in northeastern Syria|website=AP|language=en|access-date=2019-11-26|date=2019-11-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beta.theglobeandmail.com/world/article-car-bomb-kills-at-least-17-people-in-northeastern-syria-turkish/|title=Car bomb kills at least 17 people in northeastern Syria, Turkish ministry says|website=The Globe and Mail|language=en|access-date=2019-11-26|date=2019-11-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/turkey-car-bomb-kills-syria-region-controls-191126171646368.html|title=Turkey says car bomb kills several in Syria region it controls|website=Al Jazeera|language=en|access-date=2019-11-26}}</ref>\n\n===2020===\n*'''1 January 2020 -''' 16 ISIS terrorists were captured during a raid in [[Deir ez-Zor Governorate]] by the Coalition forces.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=SOJTFOIR |number=1212724668752416770 |date=January 2, 2020 |title=#DefeatDaesh UPDATE: 16 #Daesh terrorists captured during a raid in Dayr az Zawr province, #Syria, Jan. 1, 2020. The partner-led operation prevented an imminent attack against Coalition and partner forces. The investigation is ongoing. }}</ref>\n*'''14 January 2020 -''' SDF managed to kill two ISIL members, including Abu Alward Al-Iraqi, who was responsible for oil trading, in the Deir ez-Zor Governorate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.difesaesicurezza.com/en/defence-and-security/terrorism-bad-day-for-isis-in-iraq-syria-the-financial-network-has-been-hit/|title=Terrorism, bad day for Isis in Iraq-Syria. The financial network has been hit|website=Difesa & Sicurezza|date=20 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alarabiya.net/ar/arab-and-world/syria/2020/01/20/%D9%82%D8%B3%D8%AF-%D8%AA%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%86-%D9%85%D9%82%D8%AA%D9%84-%D9%85%D8%B3%D8%A4%D9%88%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%AA%D8%B1%D9%88%D9%84-%D9%88%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AA%D9%85%D9%88%D9%8A%D9%84-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%B9%D8%B4.html|title=\u0628\u0639\u062f \u0645\u0641\u062a\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0648\u0635\u0644.. \u0645\u0642\u062a\u0644 \u0631\u0623\u0633 \"\u0627\u0644\u0628\u062a\u0631\u0648\u0644\" \u0641\u064a \u062f\u0627\u0639\u0634|website=Al Arabiya|language=Arabic|date=20 January 2020}}</ref>\n*'''17 January 2020 -''' During an explosion targeting an SDF vehicle in Abu Hardoub village in the eastern countryside of Deir Ezzor, one SDF member was killed and one more injured.<ref>http://www.syriahr.com/en/?p=153139</ref>\n*'''27 January 2020 -''' Coalition [[M2 Bradley|Bradley IFVs]] were pulled out of Syria after less than two month of deployment due to unspecified reasons.<ref>[https://www.thedrive.com/the-war-zone/31979/american-bradley-armored-vehicles-were-pulled-out-of-syria-after-less-than-two-months American Bradley Armored Vehicles Were Pulled Out of Syria After Less Than Two Months]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Iraqi insurgency (2017\u2013present)]], a similar insurgency in neighboring Iraq\n*[[Second Northern Syria Buffer Zone]]\n*[[Syrian Desert campaign (December 2017\u2013present)]]\n*[[SDF insurgency in Northern Aleppo]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite journal\n|url = https://www.meforum.org/middle-east-quarterly/pdfs/58684.pdf\n|title = The End of the Syrian Civil War. Are the Insurgencies Truly Over? \n|last= McCabe \n|first= Thomas R. \n|date = Summer  2019\n|journal = Middle East Quarterly\n|publisher = [[Middle East Forum]]\n|location = Philadelphia\n|ref = harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Syrian Civil War}}\n{{Military intervention against ISIL